<FIRST>r a AM-MovieTurkeys     11-18 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movie Turkeys,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Inchon' Heads List of Decade's Most Disastrous Movies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Inchon,'' the disastrous war epic produced
by the Rev. Sung Myung Moon's Unification Church, has been selected
as the biggest box-office fiasco of the 1980s.
   In a list released Friday by the entertainment research firm
Baseline, 1982's ``Inchon,'' with Laurence Olivier and Jacqueline
Bisset, was said to have cost an estimated $46 million but made
less than $2 million at domestic movie theaters.
   The movie's net loss, $44.1 million, placed ``Inchon'' on top of
Baseline's survey.
   ``Heaven's Gate,'' widely considered the greatest flop in
Hollywood history, landed in fourth place on the top-turkey index.
Director Steven Spielberg, whose ``E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'' is
the all-time box-office champ, finished in a tie for 10th with
``Empire of the Sun.''
   The list does not take into consideration ancillary revenues
such as home video and overseas markets.
   The 10 most spectacular failures, in order:
   ``Inchon'' ($46 million cost, $1.9 million box office, $44.1
million loss); ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' ($52 million,
$9 million, $43 million); ``Ishtar'' ($45 million, $7.7 million,
$37.3 million); ``Heaven's Gate'' ($36 million, $1.5 million, $34.5
million); ``The Cotton Club'' ($46 million, $15 million, $31
million).
   ``Pirates'' ($31 million, $700,000, $30.3 million); ``Rambo
III'' ($58 million, $28 million, $30 million); ``Santa Claus'' ($45
million, $16 million, $29 million); ``Lion of the Desert'' ($30
million, $1.5 million, $28.5 million); ``Empire of the Sun'' ($38
million, $10.5 million, $27.5 million); ``Once Upon a Time in
America'' ($30 million, $2.5 million, $27.5 million).
</TEXT>
