<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Rats     11-18 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Rats,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rats Devour Precious Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rats devour or destroy nearly a
half-million tons of grain in Bangladesh each year, enough to feed
at least 3 million people in this impoverished nation, a newspaper
said.
   The destruction begins in farms and continues up to the dining
table, the Bengali-language newspaper Dainik Bangla said Friday,
quoting agricultural experts. The rats destroy about 100,000 tons
of grain in stores alone.
   More than 480,000 tons of rice and wheat _ 2.5 percent of the
country's total grain production _ is lost to the rodents annually,
the paper said.
   Bangladesh, one of the poorest nations in the world with an
annual per capita income of $160, produces about 19 million tons of
rice and wheat a year.
   The nation of 110 million people imports 1.6 million tons to 3
million tons of grain to meet yearly shortfalls.
   The rat population reaches its peak during November and December
when winter crops are harvested. During those months, authorities
launch an annual rat-killing campaign.
</TEXT>
