<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--TreasureAuction     11-18 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Treasure Auction,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasure From Sunken Galleon to be Auctioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hariot is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rare silver coins, uncut emeralds and a
70-pound silver bar from a sunken Spanish galleon are among items
to be auctioned to raise money for citrus research and 4-H programs.
   The treasure is just part of the hoard brought up from the
Nuestra Senora de Atocha off Key West by treasure hunter Mel Fisher
in 1985.
   The items were donated by two couples who got them in return for
their investments in Fisher's Treasure Salvors Inc. Organizers of
the auction, scheduled for Dec. 2 in Gainesville, won't disclose
the estimated value of the treasure.
   The donors are Eugene Lyon, a Florida historian specializing in
the Spanish colonial period, his wife, Dotie, and by Barney Greene
and his wife, Hariot. Lyon uncovered records in the Archive of the
Indies in Seville, Spain, that provided valuable clues in Fisher's
search for the treasure ship.
   Fisher will be the guest of honor at the auction.
   Proceeds will go to the University of Florida's Institute for
Food and Agricultural Sciences and Florida 4-H programs.
</TEXT>
