<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-SecretPolice     11-18 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Secret Police,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Police to Answer to Parliament; 5,000 to Lose Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's dreaded secret police, who
attacked pro-democracy protesters last month, will have a new head,
will soon answer to Parliament and will be reduced by 5,000
employees, officials say.
   The Ministry of State Security, previously under direct control
of the General Prosecutor's Office and the ruling Politburo, is in
charge of interior security and counter-intelligence. Many East
Germans fear its agents, who often have been charged with spying on
citizens.
   The state-run news agency ADN announced the changes late Friday.
   Lt. Gen. Wolfgang Schwanitz, the new head of the Office of
National Security, said ``We welcome the control of Parliament ...
and will do everything to win its trust.''
   ``We're leaving everything behind that in the past was
inappropriate or mistaken,'' Schwanitz said in an indirect
reference to past excesses, such as the beating of peaceful
demonstrators.
   He said the department would now concentrate on
counter-terrorism, investigations of ``imperialist espionage'' and
neo-Nazi activities.
</TEXT>
