<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Indians Bjt   11-18 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indians, Bjt,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Recommends Tribal Self-Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Department officials say they realize
the federal government has mishandled Indian affairs and welcome a
Senate report that recommends allowing tribes to govern themselves.
   ``Quite clearly the federal government in the past has not been
as efficient, as careful or as caring as it should have been in a
number of instances,'' Frank Bracken, Interior undersecretary, said
Friday.
   But he said the department already has begun to correct problems
identified in a 238-page report released by a special investigating
panel of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs.
   The report summarizes a two-year investigation into government
corruption relating to Indians.
   It recommends that the federal bureaucracy be broken apart to
allow tribes interested in self-determination to negotiate for
grants from the federal government much the same way as do states
and local governments.
   ``Fraud, mismanagement and corruption pervade virtually all
federal Indian programs,'' Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., chairman
of the special committee.
   He said the committee's work showed that many tribes are capable
of managing their own affairs.
   He said federal Indian agencies should continue to exist for
tribes that want the services, but in time all tribes would see the
benefits of self-government, ``assuring that the billions now
wasted on self-perpetuating federal bureaucracies will belong to
tribes themselves, to determine their own destiny.''
   ``In all, the federal budget for Indian programs equals $3.3
billion annually. Yet, surprisingly little of these funds reach the
Indian people,'' DeConcini said.
   Under the committee's proposal, the federal government would
provide an annual grant to each tribe, equal to the tribe's
proportional share of the current federal Indian budget. It would
be a permanent entitlement, in lieu of federal services from the
Bureau of Indian Affairs or other agencies.
   The tribes would have to be accountable for the funds and tribal
officials negotiating the agreements would have to be proven
representatives of their tribes.
   ``I have not yet consulted with Indian tribes about the
recommendations contained in this report and will withhold any
final comment pending consultation,'' said Eddie Brown, head of the
BIA.
   But he said he agreed with the report's finding that ``we must
take real actions and not merely offer Band-Aid solutions.''
   Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo., the only native American
in Congress, joined DeConcini and Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., and Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, in announcing the
proposals.
   ``Two hundred years of mistakes in dealing with the American
Indian can only lead to more of the same without drastic reform,''
Campbell said.
   The lawmakers said it would take a long time to put the
proposals into action, but that they would draw up legislation soon
and that Inouye, chairman of the Select Committee on Indian
Affairs, would hold extensive hearings.
   Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., who chairs the House Interior
Committee, said he had reviewed the Senate report and would work
with Inouye on legislation.
   The special committee, appointed by Inouye, held more than four
weeks of hearings last winter and spring.
   The committee staff visited more than 70 Indian tribes in 16
states, conducted about 2,000 interviews and analyzed more than 1
million documents.
   The panel examined contracting fraud, gaming operations on
reservations, child sexual abuse in federal schools, protection of
natural resources belonging to the Indians, housing, the Indian
Health Service and corruption among tribal officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
