<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-L'AmourLegacy     11-18 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-L'Amour Legacy,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Writer Leaves Legacy of Unpublished Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western novelist Louis L'Amour is dead, but
he may ride high on the best-seller lists for years thanks to
unpublished and out-of-print work.
   ``We have a couple of full-length novels and we have some
(unpublished) short story material and we have short story material
that was written for the pulps,'' Kathy L'Amour, the author's wife
of 32 years, said recently.
   ``So we're in good shape and we'll have a publishing program
well into the '90s,'' she said.
   L'Amour, a favorite of former President Reagan, died of cancer
in June 1988 at age 80.
   The unpublished works are from what he called his ``toxic dump''
_ piles of papers stacked haphazardly on the floor and desk of his
workroom.
   ``I took about seven days of randomly walking around and
randomly sampling stuff to try and find if there was any order or
not,'' said the author's son, Beau, 28. ``After that week I just
decided there wasn't any order.''
   L'Amour's ``Education of a Wandering Man,'' published a few
weeks ago, is on the New York Times and the Los Angeles Times
bestseller lists for hardcover nonfiction books.
   He was proofreading the memoir the day he died. It was his 105th
published book, including 86 novels, 16 collections of short
stories and three non-fiction books.
   A hardcover book, ``The Sackett Companion,'' and two paperback
collections of short stories, ``Lonigan'' and ``Long Ride Home,''
also have been published since his death.
</TEXT>
