<FIRST>r a PM-Names     11-18 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor James Stewart says he's been looking for a
new movie script, but he doesn't like the parts he's been offered.
   ``I keep turning scripts down because they're for grouchy
grandfathers,'' Stewart told fans Thursday at the Tattered Cover
Bookstore. ``They don't have to be grouchy.''
   Stewart, 81, was promoting his book, ``Jimmy Stewart and His
Poems,'' a collection of anecdotes and poetry that he recited on
``The Tonight Show.''
   He couldn't name any writer he considered a great influence on
his literary efforts. ``I'm just a newborn poet. I don't have
any,'' Stewart said.
   Stewart signed 300 to 350 books while several hundred fans
gathered to get a glimpse of him.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota Fats inspired ``The Hustler,''
and now an investor wants to cash in on the current pool craze by
naming a sports bar after Fats.
   ``Pool is getting to be the biggest thing in the world today,''
said Fats, whose real name is Rudolf Wanderone and who is believed
to be 76. ``Now they are opening pool rooms as fast as they can.
I'm talking multimillion-dollar joints.''
   Fats' agent, David Kastle of Tri-Media Management Group Ltd.,
said $750,000 is being sought in investment capital for the bar,
which would feature many square yards of green felt.
   Jackie Gleason portrayed Minnesota Fats in the 1961 movie, ``The
Hustler,'' starring Paul Newman. Fats has lived in Nashville for
five years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock musician Don Henley, TV talk show
host Geraldo Rivera and Minnesota Twins third baseman Gary Gaetti
took part in a radio broadcast to raise money to find Jacob
Wetterling and other missing children.
   The marathon 27{-hour broadcast on stations KXSS-FM in St. Cloud
and WLOL-FM in Minneapolis ended Friday morning with more than
$70,000 pledged for the Jacob Wetterling Fund and two missing
children's groups, the stations said.
   Jacob Wetterling was seized by a masked gunman the night of Oct.
22 while he was out riding bikes with his brother and a friend.
   FBI spokesman Byron Gigler said coverage of the Wetterling
abduction Thursday on the ``Geraldo Rivera'' show prompted about 75
calls from the public.
   The show was taped by satellite Nov. 9 at the Wetterlings' home.
Patty Wetterling, the boy's mother, later said she was upset with
the makers of the show because they focused on statistics that
showed most abducted children are abused and never seen again.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of the Atlantis space
shuttle crew were scheduled to travel to Jamaica on Monday to meet
Prime Minister Michael Manley and talk to schoolchildren about life
in space.
   Tourism Minister Frank Pringle said mission commander Capt.
Donald Williams, mission pilot Cmdr. Michael McCulley and mission
specialist Franklin Chang-Diaz accepted his invitation to visit the
Caribbean island with their families for a four-day visit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones ``Steel Wheels''
tour will hit The Boardwalk next month in a multimillion-dollar
deal with a gaming hall owned by developer Donald Trump.
   The show is being billed as ``Rolling Stones and Friends,'' and
casino executives hint many celebrities wll accompany the rock 'n'
roll band on stage.
   Tickets went on sale Friday at $38.50 each for performances Dec.
17, 19 and 20 at the city's Convention Center.
   The Dec. 19 show will be broadcast live on a pay-per-view basis
around the country, said Bernie Dillon, Trumps Sports and
Entertainment Inc. vice president.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge won't rule until next month on a lawsuit
brought by former Beatle Ringo Starr against a music producer.
   Starr won a permanent injunction from Fulton County Judge
Clarence Cooper blocking release of an album he did in 1987 and
wanted kept off the market because he was drinking heavily during
its production.
   After testimony ended Friday in the non-jury trial, court
officials said Cooper wouldn't rule until December on whether Starr
owes Memphis, Tenn., producer Chips Moman $146,239 for studio costs
and expenses.
   Starr said Wednesday there was no formal agreement and that he
understood he would not have to pay the studio expenses unless the
album were released.
   Moman contended he and Starr agreed to a three-album deal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale is
joining the Mayo Foundation Board of Trustees.
   Mondale, a partner in the Minneapolis law firm of Dorsey and
Whitney, was elected to a four-year term on the 30-member board at
a meeting Friday. The board is composed of public representatives
and Mayo Clinic physicians and administrators.
   Mondale served as vice president in the Carter administration
after serving 12 years in the U.S. Senate. He was the Democratic
presidential candidate in 1984.
</TEXT>
