<FIRST>r w PM-CableTV     11-18 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cable TV,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable TV Has `Unrestricted Monopoly,' Broadcasters Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable television companies enjoy an
``unrestricted monopoly'' that lets them overcharge customers and
seize control of sports programs, broadcast competitors contend.
   The criticism came Friday from independent and network
broadcasters at a hearing of the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation's communications subcommittee on the regulation of
the cable TV industry.
   The broadcasters say cable television operators pay nothing for
72 percent of the programming viewed by their customers because it
is supplied by networks and independent stations.
   At the same time, the broadcasters contend, the cable industry
programmers favorably treat the local cable outlets while charging
excessive rates to others.
   Five companies serve 42 percent of cable households in the
country and rates rose 29 percent in the first two years of
deregulation starting in 1987, according to the critics.
   In addition, they say, the same companies that produce cable
programs also have the cable systems, giving them control of
``conduit and content.''
   ``Cable's unrestricted monopoly operations _ its nearly free use
of the compulsory license, and its use of a triple revenue stream
of subscription rates, advertising and pay-per-view _ has led to a
completely distorted marketplace,'' said Edward O. Fritts of the
National Association of Broadcasters, which represents the networks.
   The cable industry disputed those contentions, saying rates
jumped after being kept artificially low by local regulation. It
said rates are now rising at a lower rate than inflation.
   The industry, through the National Cable Television Association,
also claims that cable helps networks by extending their reach and
improving their signals. The cable industry also says it has
increased the amount of sports programming available and blames the
team owners for jacking up the bids.
   Fritts' group supports legislation proposed by Sen. John
Danforth, R-Mo., that would re-regulate the cable industry, which
was basically de-regulated by the 1984 Cable Act.
   Danforth's bill would allow cities to regulate cable rates
unless cable companies had effective local competition and would
make it easier for cities to revoke the franchises of cable
operators who do not serve the community well.
   Preston R. Padden, president of the Association of Independent
Television Stations, claimed that cable is monopolizing sports
television. He showed the subcommittee a Los Angeles billboard
warning, ``No Cable, No Gretzky, No Cable, No Magic,'' a reference
to stars Wayne Gretzky of the Los Angeles Kings hockey team and
Magic Johnson of the Lakers basketball team.
   He also complained that such sports siphoning was occurring in
college conference sports.
   Lynn McReynolds, a spokeswoman for the cable industry group,
acknowledged that there have been ``a few instances'' where sports
events have been moved to cable.
</TEXT>
