<FIRST>u a AM-Walesa 3rdLd-Writethru a0786 11-18 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0786,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Spends Whirlwind Day In New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Walesa was...,' to UPDATE with arrival in Chicago.
^LaserPhotos NY27,30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish Solidarity leader Lech Walesa went
through a whirlwind series of meetings Friday with union officials,
Jewish leaders, politicians and businessmen, and paused to praise
American generosity.
   He told a group of state union leaders that as he was listening
to speeches that preceded his own, he came to appreciate what he
termed ``the greatness of America.''
   In Poland, he said, ``We fight, we risk, but you are in a
different situation. You don't have to fight, you don't have to
share with us, you don't have to help us.
   ``But this is not the way you behave. I thought, `Would I behave
as you do? Would I be seeing this as clearly?'''
   The Senate voted Tuesday to authorize $657 million in economic
aid to Poland over three years. On Thursday the House went further,
approving a three-year package of $846.5 million.
   After a full day of meetings in New York, Walesa flew to Chicago
late Friday, arriving at Midway Airport at 11 p.m. CST. A crowd of
about 100 people, many of them Polish-Americans who painted signs
of welcome, applauded as he stepped of a plane into blowing snow
and ice-cold temperatures.
   Walesa's meeting with New York state labor leaders began a day
that included other sessions with Jewish leaders, newspaper editors
and businessmen.
   Walesa also met Friday with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who said:
``We hardly know the man. ... But we cheer him for all the
wonderful ideas he represents.''
   Cuomo announced plans by Harper &amp; Row to publish a collection of
Abraham Lincoln's speeches and writings on democracy in Polish and
English next year.
   Cuomo said he conceived of the ``Lincoln on Democracy Project''
during a meeting in June with teachers from Poland who told him
books on Lincoln were not available in their country.
   Walesa thanked Cuomo for the Lincoln project and alluded to the
speed of political change throughout Eastern Europe: ``I don't know
if you can keep pace with translations for other languages because
the line is already forming.''
   Walesa met with about 75 Jewish leaders, several of them
survivors of the Nazi campaign to exterminate Polish Jews. One,
Reuben Gruenbaum, told Walesa of life at Auschwitz, where he was an
inmate and where his parents and grandparents were killed.
   Walesa said he hoped for resolution of a controversy over the
location of a Roman Catholic convent on the site of the death camp.
He also promised to protect the vestiges of Jewish life in Poland.
Although the nation had a Jewish population of over 3 million in
1939, only a few thousand remain today.
   Walesa received numerous gifts, which he accepted with good
humor. After he was given a set of knives, he said in mock protest:
``I'm all for nonviolent struggle. I will not use these against
anybody.'' Presented with a bust of Lincoln, he balanced it on his
head for photographers.
   He expressed regret over his inability to meet more people,
especially Polish-Americans.
   ``I would like to reach every American home, to visit every
American home,'' Walesa said. ``I would like to drink a cup of
coffee with every American girl, but time is short.''
   Walesa did manage to spend a quick 40 minutes among Poles during
a meeting with the editorial staff of the Polish Daily News, the
largest Polish daily newspaper outside Poland. He begged for some
plain talk, Pole-to-Pole.
   ``How did you feel in Congress?'' a tired-looking Walesa was
asked.
   ``Oh, my God,'' he said to a chorus of laughs. ``I have a
complex, standing next to all those greats.''
   ``But you too are great,'' offered Boleslaw Wierzbianski, the
paper's publisher.
   In the evening Walesa met more than 100 business executives at
the Forbes Gallery, repository of publisher Malcolm Forbes'
eclectic collection of artifacts, memorabilia and oddities.
   The former shipyard worker seemed most impressed by the blunt
letter President Harry Truman mailed in 1950 to a critic who had
unfavorably reviewed his daughter Margaret's singing.
   Walesa chortled as his translator read him Truman's hand-written
note. ``Someday I hope to meet you,'' Truman wrote. ``You'll need a
new nose, a lot of beefsteak for black eyes and perhaps a supporter
below!''
   Walesa concluded his visit to the gallery with yet another
impassioned plea for investment in Poland, asking the executives:
``Can we work together in business?''
   On Thursday night, Walesa accepted an award from the
International Rescue Committee, a non-sectarian, voluntary agency
that assists refugees fleeing political, religious or racial
persecution. Past recipients included Winston Churchill, George
Meany, Hubert Humphrey and Elie Wiesel.
</TEXT>
