<FIRST>r w PM-US-ElSalvador     11-18 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-El Salvador,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members of Congress Decry Violence in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic senators are threatening to slash
U.S. aid to El Salvador unless President Alfredo Cristiani can end
violence in the war-torn Central American nation.
   As an American-trained team of Salvadoran forensic experts began
an investigation of the slayings of six Jesuit priests and two
others, leftist protesters disrupted a Capitol Hill hearing,
demanding a halt to U.S. aid to Cristiani's government.
   During Friday's rancorous hearing, Sen. Christopher Dodd
declared: ``The time has come for President Cristiani to evidence
his commitment to controlling those officials within his own
government and within his own party who are in very large part
responsible for the civil conflict.''
   ``President Cristiani is either in control, or he is not ...
President Cristiani either deserves our support, or he does not,''
said Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of a Foreign Relations subcommittee on
the western hemisphere.
   Said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.: ``In an era of scarce foreign
assistance, we need to be asking what we are achieving for the
dollars sent.''
   In a statement late Friday, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash., and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
called for a return to negotiations and for an investigation of the
killings.
   ``This outrage must be investigated thoroughly, those
responsible apprehended and promptly brought to justice,'' they
said. ``Any other result would be unacceptable to the community of
nations, and in particular to the American people.''
   Bernard Aronson, the State Department's senior official for
Latin American policy, agreed that without improvements, ``the
policy won't go on.'' But he blamed the current conflict and human
rights abuses that have accompanied it on rebel provocations.
   ``Implicit in our support is a demand that they make real
progress in human rights,'' he said. ``Things have to change in
Salvador.''
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which has been
fighting El Salvador's government in a bloody civil war for the
past decade, has undertaken assassinations designed to lure
right-wing death squads ``out of the closet,'' Aronson said.
   ``Their strategy is to polarize'' the country and cripple the
new government of Cristiani, the rightist president, Aronson said.
   And he said the purpose of the current FMLN offensive in the
capital of San Salvador has been not to strengthen the rebels'
negotiating position, as the FMLN contends, but ``to take total
power.''
   ``Had they succeeded ... another ally of Cuba and Nicaragua,
holding power with Soviet bloc weaponry, would have been firmly
entrenched in Central America,'' Aronson said.
   He said the murders early Thursday likely were the work of
violent right-wing death squads blamed for most of the 70,000
deaths that have occurred during the country's civil war. But
Aronson cautioned against leaping to conclusions before the outcome
of the U.S.-supported criminal investigation.
   ``We want this crime investigated fully, swiftly and those
responsible punished with the full force of the law,'' he said.
``Promises will not satisfy the high standards that President
Cristiani proclaimed in his inaugural address, they will not
satisfy the Salvadoran people and they will not satisfy the United
States.''
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler noted that
Cristiani had assured U.S. Ambassador William Walker that even if
members of the Salvadoran armed forces were involved, ``they will
feel the full weight of the law.''
   ``The United States expects him to meet that commitment,'' she
said.
   In another development, a U.S. general who drafted a classified
military strategy for El Salvador said the guerrillas cannot be
defeated on the battlefield, and said the war drags on because of
corruption within the U.S.-backed government.
   Gen. Fred Woerner, who until recently headed the U.S. Southern
Command in Panama, also said the murder of six Roman Catholic
priests most likely was the work of the radical right wing acting
without the support or tacit consent of the conservative government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
