<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GunSales     11-18 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Sales,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recommended Gun-Control Program Hugely Expensive, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program of instant background checks for
gun-buyers _ intended to prevent sales to convicted felons _ would
be so expensive the Justice Department isn't expected to recommend
immediate implementation, congressional sources say.
   Such instant background checks could cost up to $27 billion to
begin, sources said Friday.
   The Justice Department recommendation, due to be released
Monday, suggests such a program but does not call for immediate
implementation ``because of lack of funds and lack of
computerization'' of all the criminal records, one source said.
   The computerization of complete information, including final
dispensation of charges that often are not included in law
enforcement computer systems now used, ``will cost tens of millions
of dollars and will delay this for several years,'' said that
source, who said he was informed of the report by Justice
Department officials.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel declined to comment on
the report's contents, saying, ``It's still in the process of being
reviewed. Until the review's been completed, there's no final
decision.''
   The report was required by an Anti-Drug Abuse Act amendment that
had been approved as an alternative to another measure that would
have required a seven-day waiting period _ while authorities
conducted background checks if they wished _ before a person could
buy a gun.
   The Justice Department was required to provide a report to
Congress by Nov. 18 on its recommendations for preventing sales of
guns to felons. Implementation was to begin Dec. 1.
   Rep. Edward Feighan, D-Ohio, who introduced the waiting-period
measure _ dubbed the ``Brady amendment'' in reference to former
presidential press secretary James Brady who was wounded by an
assailant trying to shoot then-President Reagan _ said Friday,
``The report is a compelling argument for immediate enactment of
the Brady Bill.''
   ``The report acknowledges that a point-of-sale check will be
enormously expensive and cannot be implemented in the relatively
near future,'' he said. ``I appreciate the attorney general's
effort, but I am bitterly disappointed that we have lost a year's
time in saving the lives of Americans.''
   Selecting the option of instantaneous checks at the point of
sale would be a move toward one of the most expensive undertakings
possible at a time when the federal government is strapped for
funds, he said.
   Start-up costs for an immediate, live scan of fingerprints by
gun dealers would be $9.6 billion to $27 billion, according to the
report by the Task Force on Felon Identification in Firearm Sales
published in the Federal Register on Oct. 25.
   Also being recommended, according to the sources, are
point-of-sale telephone checks by gun dealers to authorities with
access to computerized information and similar telephone checks to
an intermediate computer with the same access to information.
   Those would have start-up costs of $36 million to $44 million,
according to the task force.
   Runkel said in June that Attorney General Dick Thornburgh had
rejected another option _ the issuance of firearm owner's
identification cards following background checks _ that would have
had start-up costs of $148 million to $153 million.
   These costs do not include the original computerization of
information, which the task force said will involve ``substantial
resources.'' It did not give a precise figure.
   Gwen Fitzgerald of Handgun Control Inc. criticized the
recommendations because they call for no immediate action.
   ``This removes every obstacle for not passing the Brady Bill as
soon as possible,'' Fitzgerald said. ``Last September, during the
vote on the Brady amendment, and for an entire year, Congress
didn't have to deal with this because they had the McCollum
Amendment (the one enacted) to hide behind. They were waiting for
this announcement.''
   ``It's now clear that nothing is going to happen anytime soon
under this directive, which means that convicted felons are still
buying guns over the counter in 28 states,'' she said, adding that
the rest of the states have some kind of background check or
waiting period before an individual can buy a gun.
   The McCollum Amendment is named for Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
