<FIRST>r w PM-Senators-Lincoln     11-18 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senators-Lincoln,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Hires Attorney to Investigate Senators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee investigation of
five senators is gathering steam with the hiring of a prominent
lawyer, who will gather evidence to help the panel decide its next
move.
   Robert S. Bennett of Washington, D.C., was retained Friday to
``assist in obtaining and analyzing additional information'' on the
five senators who met with federal regulators on behalf of the
failing Lincoln Savings and Loan _ after receiving campaign
contributions from the head of the thrift.
   The committee said Bennett also will work on the case of Sen.
Alfonse M. D'Amato, R-N.Y., accused in a complaint by a former
election opponent of violating rules in the federal housing scandal
and other matters.
   Committee Chairman Howell Heflin, D-Ala., and Vice Chairman
Warren Rudman, R-N.H., said Bennett will ``assist the committee in
determining whether to proceed to a preliminary inquiry'' in both
matters.
   The preliminary proceeding is the first of three stages of a
formal committee investigation, and Rudman said it could take
several months to decide whether this stage will be approved.
   The hiring of Bennett ``does not suggest in any way that the
committee has found any indication of wrongdoing, or that a
violation of any rule or law has occurred,'' the two senators said
in a statement.
   All five in the savings and loan case have denied wrongdoing:
Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; John
Glenn, D-Ohio; John McCain, R-Ariz., and Donald W. Riegle Jr.,
D-Mich. So has D'Amato.
   After the announcement, Glenn said it ``was expected,'' and
D'Amato commented, ``Sure, let them do it. I'm not concerned.''
Cranston said the outside counsel was ``not necessary'' but pledged
his ``utmost cooperation.'' ``I am confident the outside counsel
will concur with our view that my conduct was entirely proper,''
Cranston added.
   The five senators who met with regulators did so while banking
investigators were examining the collapsing Irvine, Calif., savings
institution in 1987. The chairman of the thrift, Charles H. Keating
Jr., gave $1.3 million to the senators' campaigns or their
political causes in the mid-1980s.
   Riegle, DeConcini and Glenn also issued fresh declarations of
innocence during the day.
   The five men are among the most powerful in the Senate _ with
Cranston the No. 2 Democrat and Riegle and Glenn holding committee
chairmanships.
   Glenn told reporters he never discussed any deals for Keating
when participating in discussions with the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board about Lincoln.
   ``I do not recall that there was any deal whatsoever that was
ever made. I was not party to any deal, did not agree to any
deal,'' said Glenn, chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee.
   DeConcini said, ```I'm prepared and we'll cooperate with the
independent counsel. If that's the decision of the committee, it
would be very positive to bring out all the facts related to the
... charge.
   ``I hope the independent counsel will expedite it, or rapidly
bring it to conclusion,'' DeConcini said.
   Riegle, the Senate Banking Committee chairman, commented, ``I
strongly support whatever level of inquiry the Senate Ethics
Committee feels is appropriate. Their review will show my conduct
in this matter to have been ethical and proper at all times.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
