<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Pay Bjt   11-18 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Pay, Bjt,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Pay Raise, Ethics Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $31,000-plus pay raise for the House _ but
only $8,900 for the Senate _ is on its way to President Bush's desk
after careening through Congress in just two days.
   The Senate voted 56-43 Friday night to approve the bill, but
only after deciding at the last minute that it couldn't take the
poltical risk of the bigger House-passed pay raise. Instead,
senators would keep taking honoraria from interest groups, a
much-criticized practice eliminated by the House.
   ``We have done exactly the wrong thing tonight. We have
failed,'' said Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo.
   But the Senate didn't cut back the raise that applies to the
House, federal judges and top government executives, and the House
early today gave the measure final approval and shipped the package
to the president. The House gave its approval in a voice vote at
nearly 1:30 a.m. with whistling and cheers in the chamber.
   Bush has said he would sign the bill, which includes a series of
reforms of congressional and government-wide ethics rules.
   For the House and the other top officials, salaries would rise
from the current $89,500 to $96,600 by Jan. 1 and to at least
$120,800 and probably closer to $125,000 a year later, depending on
government-wide cost of living adjustments at that time.
   In 1991, when a 25 percent pay boost making up the bulk of the
increase takes effect, the practice of House members accepting
speaking fees for appearances before interest groups will end and
Congress' other outside earnings will be limited.
   The Senate opted for taking a 9.9 percent raise on Jan. 1 to
$98,400, and gradually reducing the amount of honoraria its members
can keep. Currently, they can keep speaking fees up to 40 percent
of their salaries.
   The Senate decision meant different salary scales for the Senate
and House, with the Senate earning more at first and the House
passing it later.
   That would be unusual but not unprecedented. From Dec. 21, 1982,
to July 1, 1983, the Senate was paid $60,662 and the House $69,800.
   Besides the pay-honoraria issue, the legislation contains a
broad range of changes in ethics rules.
   No lobbying anywhere in the legislative branch would be allowed
for one year. Cabinet-level officials at the White House also would
face a similar ban on lobbying in their branch of government.
   In addition to banning honoraria, the legislation would put new
restrictions on gifts and free travel lawmakers and other
government officials can accept from people outside their immediate
family.
   The legislation also would end in 1993 the ability of House
members elected before 1980 to, upon retirement, transfer the
balance of their campaign treasuries for personal use.
</TEXT>
