<FIRST>r a PM-PaAbortion     11-18 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pa Abortion,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Governor Signs Bill Restricting Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion Bill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Robert P. Casey signed the nation's
toughest abortion controls into law despite warnings from
abortion-rights advocates that it could cost him re-election.
   When the bill signed Friday takes effect in 60 days, women in
the state will be banned from obtaining abortions after the 24th
week of pregnancy in most cases and will have to inform their
husbands if they plan an abortion.
   Pennsylvania is the first state to take advantage of a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling in July that gave states more leeway to make
their own abortion laws.
   Casey, a Democrat, said he was aware abortion-rights activists
would campaign heavily on the issue next year, when he is expected
to seek re-election and could face a Republican who supports a
woman's right to have an abortion.
   ``I hope that no one makes it a single-issue campaign. I
certainly don't plan to run a single-issue campaign,'' Casey said.
   He said the provisions of the law ``are appropriate and
reasonable, given the enormity of the decision any woman faces when
she considers having an abortion. The overwhelming votes in the
state House and Senate convince me that the vast majority of our
people will agree.''
   The abortion measure passed the House 143-58 last month; the
Senate approved the bill 33-17 on Tuesday.
   ``It gives a tremendous shot in the arm to the national pro-life
movement,'' said state Rep. Stephen Freind, the Republican who led
the anti-abortion fight in the Legislature.
   Jenny Daughtry, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights League chapter in Pennsylvania, said the bill was ``cruel
and demeaning and a direct attack on women's constitutional
rights.''
   ``Governor Casey's signature on this bill is an affront to the
health, welfare and interest of all Pennsylvanians. Pennsylvanians
will express their outrage over this attack on their rights at the
voting booth next November,'' she said.
   In a statement, Auditor General Barbara Hafer, the front-runner
for the Republican nomination, said she would have vetoed the bill.
   ``I believe that the bill does not reflect the will of the
majority of Pennsylvanians or, in fact, of Americans,'' Hafer said.
   Howard Fetterhoff, executive director of the Pennsylvania
Catholic Conference, said Casey's action ``demonstrated his
life-long commitment to what he believes: that innocent human life,
and in this case, the unborn ... are worthy of protection.''
   The new law also prohibits abortions based on the fetus' sex;
regulates the medical use of tissue from aborted fetuses and
mandates women wait 24 hours to get an abortion. Doctors will have
to inform women about the procedure before performing an abortion
and explain risks and alternatives.
   The law also carries stiff penalties for doctors that violate
the regulations; a conviction under the sex-selection ban or
24-week provision could result in up to seven years in prison and
$15,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
