<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Insurance     11-18 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Insurance,0197</SECOND>
<UNK>Judge Permits Lawsuit over Insruance Coverage for Abortion</UNK>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge allowed a class-action
lawsuit that challenges a state law restricting insurance for
abortions.
   The suit approved Friday by Judge Scott O. Wright challenges a
1983 statute that forbids insurance policies covering elective
abortions except by an optional rider that requires payment of an
additional premium.
   It was filed in July by Jane Coe, a pseudonym to protect the
identity of a married 39-year-old St. Louis-area woman. It names
Lewis Melahan, director of the Missouri Department of Insurance,
and William Webster, Missouri attorney general, as defendants.
   Earlier this year, Coe was pregnant carrying a fetus with
Trisomy 13 syndrome, a condition marked by congenital
malformations, including multiple-organ systems and severe mental
retardation, according to the complaint.
   Only 18 percent of such fetuses that survive birth live more
than a year, the complaint said.
   Coe underwent an abortion that resulted in medical fees of
$1,000, the suit said. Although she was insured under a
comprehensive health care policy issued by Blue Cross of Missouri,
coverage for the abortion was denied as a result of the law.
</TEXT>
