<HEAD>Bringing Popgun For Show-And-Tell Gets 5-Year-Old Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAZELHURST, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 5-year-old Walt Crosby brought his
new wooden popgun to kindergarten for show-and-tell, school
officials showed him the door for violating a policy against
weapons on campus.
   ``I think somebody overreacted,'' said Wiley Crosby, Walt's
father, after the boy was suspended for one day from Jeff Davis
County Eleentary School. ``I think they need to use a little common
sense when dealing with a 5-year-old.''
   The gun is the type from which a cork pops and dangles on a
string.
   Fay Dickens, interim school superintendent for Jeff Davis
County, said the child was suspended Nov. 10 under a policy that
prohibits ``dangerous weapons, toy weapons and look-alike weapons''
and applies to all public school students, regardless of age.
   ``Five-year-olds are not excluded,'' Ms. Dickens said. ``And
with a popgun, the string could break and the cork could put out
another person's eye.''
   Ms. Dickens said another child was sent home for bringing a
water pistol to school.
