<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Budget Bjt   11-18 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Budget, Bjt,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators Repeal Catastrophic Coverage, Near Deficit-Reduction
Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators from the House and Senate are
calling for repeal of catastrophic health coverage for retirees and
nearing agreement on a compromise deficit-reduction package.
   Final action on those two bills, which could come Sunday, would
free Congress to adjourn for the year.
   Senior tax-writers in both houses agreed early today to kill the
catastrophic program, which was enacted with great fanfare less
than 18 months ago in an effort to protect retirees from being
bankrupted by costs of a major illness.
   But two Republican senators who had wanted to scale back the
program said they will work to defeat the repeal agreement. Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., promised to use every parliamentary tactic
available in an effort to prevent repeal, which he said would be an
incredible injustice.
   Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas agreed with McCain that
repeal should be blocked. That means the Senate could be facing a
filibuster against repeal just as it tries to shut down for the
year.
   Repeal would leave many of the 32 million retirees with no
protection against catastrophic bills for hospital stays, skilled
nursing care, prescription drugs and doctors' fees.
   The Senate Finance Committee approved a compromise
deficit-reduction plan worked out on Friday by its chairman, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and the chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill. The plan still was
subject to final approval by the Ways and Means Committee before
being put to a vote in the House and Senate on Sunday.
   The committees were unable to estimate immediately how much the
package would reduce the deficit. The tax committees' portion of
the plan includes several minor tax increases and targeted cuts in
Medicare reimbursements to doctors and hospitals.
   The tax increase affecting the greatest number of people would
extend permanently the 3 percent tax on local and long-distance
telephone service which is due to expire at the end of 1990.
   Even while Democratic leaders were working out a package of
deficit cuts, GOP lawmakers pronounced the Democratic effort
inadequate.
   ``They appear to be short'' of the savings President Bush is
insisting on, Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, ranking Republican on
the Senate Finance Committee, said of the Democratic package. Bush
has threatened to veto any bill that falls short of cutting $14
billion from this year's government shortfall.
   The Democratic leaders were aiming to slice at least $12 billion
from the federal budget deficit.
   It seemed all but certain that in addition to the
deficit-reduction bill, additional savings would come from allowing
the Gramm-Rudman law's constraints on federal spending to remain in
effect for at least two months.
   Because Congress and President Bush have been unable to agree to
a budget-cutting package, the Gramm-Rudman law since Oct. 1 has
trimmed about 5 percent from most domestic programs and about 4
percent from defense spending.
   Lawmakers are virtually certain to allow the Gramm-Rudman cuts
that have already been made to stand, and perhaps to extend them to
about Jan. 1. But legislators planned to halt any further
reductions under the law.
   Leaving the cuts in effect saves the government roughly $1
billion per month.
   The Senate passed a bill claiming $14 billion in savings on Oct.
13, eight days after the House approved an $11 billion version of
the measure. But the House bill was loaded with unrelated
provisions, such as changes in the Medicare and Medicaid programs.
A large portion of the negotiations between the two houses have
been over how to deal with the extraneous House provisions.
   Bush has threatened to veto any deficit-cutting bill that relies
on phony savings gimmicks, although lawmakers say they believe they
can fashion a bill he would sign.
   Some artifices are expected to remain in the measure anyway,
such as a claimed savings of $1.7 billion by not counting money
lost by the Postal Service in the government's budget calculations.
   The Bush administration says it expects the deficit for the 1990
fiscal year, which began Oct. 1, to reach $116 billion.
Congressional experts have put the figure closer to $141 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
