<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Bridge 1stLd-Writethru a0712 11-18 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Bridge, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0712,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Reopens for First Time Since Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with bridge reopening. Pick up
3rd graf pvs: `But the true...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, its
earthquake -ruptured section repaired and sporting new silver
paint, was reopened Friday night in a din of blaring horns and
cheers.
   Six California Highway Patrol cruisers, sirens whining, and 13
private tow trucks, yellow lights flashing, led a parade on a 35
mph, 10-minute trip across the upper deck to San Francisco.
   Five American Red Cross vehicles followed the tow trucks across
the bridge. Westbound motorists were kept a mile back from the
bridge on nearby freeways until after the official opening. It was
the first traffic on the span since 7.1-magnitude quake struck
Northern California on Oct. 17, killing 66 people, most of them on
a freeway that collapsed in Oakland.
   But the true test for the 8.5-mile Bay Bridge _ the longest
high-level span in the world _ will come Monday when thousands of
commuters are expected to return to the vital artery. The bridge
carried more than 260,000 vehicles every weekday before the quake
sent a 250-ton piece of the upper deck smashing onto the lower
deck, killing one driver.
   Transportation officials warned that gridlock will result if too
many commuters abandon mass transit on Monday because several key
approaches to the bridge remain closed on either side of the bay.
   ``We had a traffic problem here even before the quake,'' said
Bob Halligan, spokesman for the state Department of Transportation.
``Now people will have to decide if they want to sit in their cars
for hours on the Bay Bridge, or do they want to get to work?''
   Halligan said Highway Patrol vehicles would lead motorists
across at the reopening to restrain any drivers who might be
tempted to set a speed record over the empty bridge.
   The quake forced thousands of commuters to switch to alternative
means of transit or take a longer route across the bay by using
four other main toll bridges in the area.
   A fleet of 20 ferry boats was amassed during the crisis,
recalling the days when even bigger ferries were common sights on
the bay.
   Terry Koenig, marketing manager of Red &amp; White Fleet, said his
company and Blue &amp; Gold, the other ferry operator, have been
averaging about 15,000 riders a day. The operators have enough
money from a $2 million emergency grant from the state to maintain
increased service through Jan. 15.
   Ridership also skyrocketed on the Bay Area Rapid Transit system,
which has a line running under the bay. On Wednesday, BART carried
355,131 people, besting the previous record of 352,696 set Nov. 3.
   One motorist who opted for BART, Bob Eberle of Emeryville, said
he plans to go back to his car.
   ``There was too much wait,'' he said as he emerged from a subway
station in San Francisco on Friday. ``With my car, I can get right
on the bridge.'' Eberle also complained there wasn't enough parking
space at the BART station in his neighborhood.
   But the transit system was a winner as far as Stanley Collis was
concerned. ``I'm going to stick with BART,'' said Collis, who works
at the state building in San Francisco. ``It's cheaper than finding
a parking space and I get a chance to read or sleep.''
   The gridlock warnings weren't the first since the quake.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos warned ``the largest traffic jams
in the history of the area'' would develop on Oct. 23, the first
full-blown rush hour to follow the devastating earthquake.
   The traffic jams didn't happen, despite heavy rain and wind
gusts over 50 mph. Officials said many people got up early for work
and helped spread out the rush hour.
</TEXT>
