<FIRST>r w PM-US-VietnamClaims     11-18 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Vietnam Claims,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Heeds Hanoi Warning Against Claims Payment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam says it may hold up settlement of
Vietnam War-related humanitarian issues if U.S. property claims are
paid from frozen assets of the fallen Saigon government, members of
Congress are being told.
   The main humanitarian issues involve efforts to account for U.S.
servicemen still missing after the war and emigration permission
for tens of thousands of people stranded after the fall of Saigon
in 1975. They include Vietnamese people who worked for Americans
during the war or their close relatives and ``Amerasian'' children
fathered by American servicemen.
   Hanoi authorities ``have given very clear indication that it
would impede progress'' on such humanitarian matters if the United
States settled citizen claims against Vietnam using more than $200
million in blocked U.S. accounts of the former South Vietnam
government, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State David F. Lambertson
told a House panel on Friday.
   State and Treasury Department officials strongly opposed pending
legislation to seize the frozen funds to pay 192 American
claimants. The U.S. Foreign Claims Settlement Commission ruled in
1986 that they were entitled to eventual reimbursement for $99
million worth of property lost during the fall of Saigon plus 6
percent annual interest.
   The claims include corporate assets, personal effects and unsold
farmland left behind by U.S. government employees and civilians who
heeded superiors' pleas to stay on until it was too late for
orderly departure, said the claimants' lawyer, Roderick M. Hills.
   R.R. Newcomb, Treasury director of foreign assets control, said
seizing the blocked assets unilaterally was a drastic step that
would undermine the U.S. position that ``foreign property _ whether
U.S. property abroad or foreign property in the U.S.'' cannot be
taken without compensation.
   Paying the private claims now could also jeopardize future
settlement of U.S. government claims against the Saigon accounts,
he added.
   Hanoi's position is that claims are matters for negotiation, not
unilateral decision, Lambertson told the Asian and Pacific affairs
subcommittee hearing.
   But the U.S. cannot now negotiate, he explained, under its
policy of holding up normalization with Vietnam until Hanoi
cooperates in a comprehensive solution of the Cambodian question.
   American interests are strongly involved in the pending
humanitarian issues, said the State Department's chief of refugee
programs, Assistant Secretary Robert L. Funseth.
</TEXT>
