<FIRST>r a PM-NavyStand-Down     11-18 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Stand-Down,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Stand-Down Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two new accidents, including a fire aboard a
nuclear-powered submarine, were reported on the last day of the
Navy's service-wide safety review that was ordered after a rash of
mishaps.
   The fire aboard the submarine USS Finback broke out in
insulation around an engine on the attack submarine, forcing the
vessel to cut short sea trials, Lt. Cmdr. Bill Sonntag of the
Submarine Atlantic Forces said Friday.
   The fire _ which broke out Wednesday _ was quickly extinguished
without danger of a nuclear accident and without injuries, he said.
   The Norfolk-based Finback returned to port Thursday to repair
the insulation, and the submarine's crew participated in the safety
review, Sonntag said.
   In the second accident, which occurred Friday, mechanical
problems forced a TA-4J training jet to ditch in the Gulf of Mexico
south of Pensacola, Fla., a Navy spokesman said. The two pilots
ejected safely.
   The stand-down halting all normal operations and training was
ordered Tuesday by Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III and Adm.
Carlisle A.H. Trost, chief of naval operations, after a three-week
string of accidents.
   ``Never in the history of the modern Navy, have so many mishaps
happened at one time,'' said Capt. Ferguson Norton, commander of
the Naval Safety Center at the Norfolk Naval Station and the Navy's
top safety officer.
   But Norton said the accidents weren't related.
   Since Oct. 29, 10 people have been killed or lost at sea and at
least 71 injured in accidents ranging from men washed overboard to
plane crashes, ship fires and the accidental bombing of a cruiser.
   Trost ordered all Navy units to hold the 48 hours of safety
review sometime over a 72-hour period beginning Tuesday; the last
reviews concluded Friday.
   Trost ordered commanders to report findings from the safety
review to him. Navy spokesmen had no details on what the reports
contained.
   Navy officials said the stand-down wasn't ordered because the
service was operating in an unsafe manner, but because Garrett and
Trost wanted to ensure that everything that could be done was being
done to protect servicemen.
   Despite the recent crop of mishaps, 1989 is the service's safest
year on record so far, with 69 major accidents reported, according
to the Navy. In 1984, 118 major accidents were reported. Every year
since then, the numbers have declined.
   The Navy defines a major accident as one that causes a fatality
or $1 million or more in damage.
   Where 1989 varies from the previous five years is in fatalities.
There have been 102 this year, including the 47 sailors killed in
the April 19 gun turret explosion aboard the battleship USS Iowa.
In 1984, 64 people died in accidents.
</TEXT>
