<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-18 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The venerable board game ``Monopoly'' is coming
to TV as a game show.
   King World Productions, maker of the syndicated ``Wheel of
Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy!'' shows, said Friday that the new show
would be available next fall.
   The TV version of ``Monopoly'' will be hosted by Peter Tomarken,
who for three years hosted ``Press Your Luck'' on CBS.
   The original ``Monopoly'' game first was sold in 1935. According
to Parker Brothers, which owns the game, it now is sold in more
than 80 countries and has been translated into 23 languages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters got a holiday-season surprise when bus
driver Louis Cordova stopped in the middle of his run, got out and
returned a short while later to pass out three dozen doughnuts.
   Smiles broke out among the 25 riders, but Cordova said his
surprise treat Thursday morning wasn't any big deal.
   ``I didn't give out those doughnuts to get my name in the paper,
and I certainly don't want my picture taken,'' the 45-year-old
driver said. ``Simply seeing those smiles on peoples' faces and
knowing that they appreciated it was reward enough.''
   Cordova, who has been driving city buses since 1972, often
passes out holiday goodies, said Terry Vicek, a manager with the
Denver-area Regional Transportation District.
</TEXT>
