<FIRST>r a PM-PropaneFire     11-18 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Propane Fire,0220</SECOND>
<UNK>Residents Back Home After Propane Fire Extinguished</UNK>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People forced from their homes by a fire that
burned for 24 hours at a propane storage area were allowed home
after oilfield firefighting experts helped extinguish the blaze.
   About 500 people _ half the town _ returned home Friday.
   They were evacuated Thursday after propane leaking from a
17-acre underground storage cavern ignited, shooting flames 200
feet into the air.
   After one attempt to put out the fire at the Williams Pipe Line
Co. failed, local firefighters moved a mile away and let it burn
until the team from Boots &amp; Coots, Inc. could arrive from Houston.
   The fire was put out when 4,000 gallons of water was pumped into
the limestone cavern to contain the propane gas.
   ``They're good,'' Carthage fire Lt. Donovan Whitman said of
oilwell firefighters David Thompson and Ace Barnes. ``We couldn't
have done it without them.
   Fifteen trucks brought in water, which was emptied into a nearby
farmer's pond. Three pumper trucks were used to build up enough
pressure to move the water from the pond to the cavern.
   A similar effort failed Thursday because there wasn't enough
water available, Whitman said.
   Jasper is 120 miles south of Kansas City.
</TEXT>
