<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Moslems     11-18 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Moslems,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armed Men Kill Five Before Autonomy Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ZBO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen today massacred a Moslem
militiaman and four relatives a day before southern Filipinos vote
on a regional autonomy plan offered in response to Moslem demands,
police said.
   Elsewhere on southern Mindanao island, two bombs exploded. There
were no reports of injury.
   Voters in 13 southern provinces and nine cities decide Sunday
whether to join a regional autonomous government for the southern
Philippines.
   President Corazon Aquino had made the offer to placate demands
for self-rule by an estimated 4 million Moslems.
   Moslems who have waged a nearly 20-year-old insurgency have
rejected the plan as inadequate.
   Col. Jesus Almadin, police area commander, said the massacre
took place shortly after midnight in a village on the outskirts of
Zamboanga, a port city about 540 miles south of Manila.
   Almadin said 15 unidentified men sprayed automatic weapon fire
and exploded several grenades in the house of a Moslem militiaman,
killing him, his wife, two sons and a daughter-in-law.
   The militiaman's 9-year-old son was critically wounded and two
other relatives escaped unhurt, Almadin added.
   The assailants set the house on fire before escaping, he said.
   ``I think this (massacre) may aggravate the situation,'' Almadin
said. ``The Christians could be blamed, and the Moslems could
retaliate.''
   Ustadz Jain Jali, spokesman of the Moslem Moro National
Liberation Front, said the incident was perpetrated by Christian
militiamen who killed the Moslem militiaman because of an ``old
family feud.''
   ``It seems that they (the killers) were taking advantage of the
tension in the area,'' Jali said, referring to violent incidents
linked to the plebiscite.
   Almadin also said a small incendiary bomb exploded just outside
Zamboanga's airport. In Lanao del Sur province, a bomb exploded in
the provincial capitol building in Marawi city, destroying election
materials. There were no reports of casualties, police said.
   Marawi is about 175 miles northeast of Zamboanga and 510 miles
southeast of Manila, the nation's capital.
   On Friday, 50,000 military and police were placed on full alert
in wide areas of Mindanao because of fear the rebels might escalate
attacks as the plebiscite nears.
   Many Christian voters are expected to reject the autonomy plan,
and Moslems form a majority in only five impoverished and
geographically separated provinces. Only 28 percent of the 3.9
million registered voters are Moslem, election records show.
   On Thursday, Mrs. Aquino urged people to take part in the
referendum but did not specifically ask them to endorse her plan.
   Mrs. Aquino forged a cease-fire with the Moslem rebels in 1986.
Peace talks collapsed in May 1987, but the cease-fire generally has
held.
   Before the Moslem rebellion peaked in the mid-1970s, an
estimated 50,000 people were killed and thousands more fled to the
nearby Malaysian state of Sabah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
