<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     11-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Company Breaks Off Negotiations With Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes for an end to a bitter 14-week-old phone
strike were dashed today when Nynex Corp. broke off negotiations
with one of two striking unions, saying the workers had reneged on
an earlier agreement.
   No further talks were scheduled with the Communications Workers
of America, said John Bonomo, spokesman for Nynex, which serves
10.5 million customers in New York and New England.
   The CWA represents 40,000 workers at New York Telephone, the
subsidiary of Nynex that serves New York state. Another 20,000
workers represented by the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers work for New England Telephone, the other Nynex subsidiary.
   In Boston, negotiators for IBEW and New England Telephone said
they had reached tentative agreement on local issues just before a
midnight deadline Friday night. Officials of both sides said IBEW
members would vote Sunday on that proposed agreement.
   It was unclear if the CWA and IBEW could settle independently of
each other.
   Bonomo said one of the stumbling blocks in reaching a settlement
with the CWA was health care for retired workers, an issue Nynex
said had been resolved in a tentative settlement reached Monday. At
that time, the company said it would pay all health benefits if the
unions gave up annual lump-sum bonuses and a profit-sharing plan.
   CWA spokesman Bob Masters said the talks broke down Friday
because of the company's insistence that the tentative agreement be
signed before other details could be worked out.
   The unfinished details included company demands for a longer
work week at the same pay and an extension of company rights to
hire temporary workers, Masters said.
   ``The company walked away from the table,'' he said.
   The talks were held at a hotel in Rye Brook, a town just north
of New York City.
   The strike began Aug. 6 in tandem with strikes at three other
regional telephone companies around the United States. Those
strikes were all resolved within a few weeks.
   The strike has delayed directory assistance, repairs and
installation for Nynex's 10.5 million customers in New York,
Connecticut, Rhode Island, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Vermont
and Maine.
</TEXT>
