<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Israel     11-18 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Israel,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Ethiopia Providing Israel Naval Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia will provide Israel with naval
facilities in the Red Sea as part of the deal that led to
diplomatic relations between the two nations, a Sudanese government
newspaper reported.
   The newspaper, Al-Engaz Al-Watani, also said Friday the deal
allows 22,000 Ethiopian Jews to leave for Israel and pledges
Israeli military experts to help Ethiopia's Marxist government put
down secession movements in the north.
   However, other reports say there are no more than 18,000 Jews
left in Ethiopia.
   Ethiopia two weeks ago restored diplomatic relations with Israel
after severing them over the 1973 Middle East war.
   The Khartoum daily quoted diplomatic sources for its report but
gave no names. Ethiopia supports rebels in southern Sudan and has
been on bad terms with the Sudanese government for years.
   There was no immediate comment from the Israeli government.
   The New York Times has reported that Israeli military advisers
are at an Ethiopian air force base. It said Ethiopia turned to the
Israelis for help against rebels in Eritrea and Tigre provinces
after its main supplier, the Soviet Union, demanded national
reconciliation.
   Al-Engaz Al-Watani said its diplomatic sources reported that the
Soviet government gave Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam
the go-ahead to resume relations with Israel.
   The paper said resumption of relations amounted to an exchange
of Israeli military help for the Jews, called Falashas, and naval
facilities. But it gave no specifics of military help Israel will
give under the purported deal.
   It said the ``military and maritime facilities'' are to be on
the islands of Sali and Khaja in the Bab al-Mandab, the southern
mouth of the Red Sea. The report did not say what sort of
facilities would be included or whether they would constitute
full-scale bases.
   In the 1973 war, Egypt and South Yemen sealed the area to
Israeli ships in an attempt to neutralize Israel's control of the
Strait of Tiran at the tip of the Sinai Peninsula.
   The figure of 22,000 Ethiopian Jews to go to Israel clashes with
other estimates of the number left after a controversial
U.S.-sponsored airlift spirited out around 8,000 Falashas in
November 1984-January 1985.
   Israel's Public Council for Ethiopian Jews estimates that only
18,000 remain, and the Ethiopian government sets the figure at
16,000.
   The mid-1980s operation, which incensed Arab governments who
charged that it helped their enemy Israel, went via airstrips in
Sudan.
   The day after Israeli-Ethiopian ties were restored, Israel's
foreign minister, Moshe Arens, said the move would ``facilitate the
ability to deal directly with the government of Ethiopia to bring
out the remainder of Ethiopian Jewry to Israel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
