<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0479 11-18 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Third Of Capital Residents Said Trapped By Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf `Dozens of...' with 1 graf to ADD that arrested
Lutherans released. Pickup 10th graf `Union halls...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SAL1, SAL2, LaserColor SAL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third of this capital's 1
million people were reportedly trapped without food and water after
a week of fighting between leftist rebels and government troops.
   Journalists in the eastern provincial capital of San Miguel
reported heavy fighting in that city and on a nearby bridge Friday
night. They had no estimates of deaths or injuries in the city 85
miles east of the capital.
   Hospital and military sources say more than 800 people have been
killed and and 2,000 wounded since the Marxist-led rebels launched
the offensive against the rightist government on Nov 11.
   There was a lull in the fighting in San Salvador on Friday night
and early today, with only occasional bursts of gunfire. However,
the capital has suffered the worst fighting of the 10-year-old
civil war over the past week.
   Chavez Mena of the center-left Christian Democratic Party said
300,000 people, nearly a third of the capital's population, have
been cut off from food and water and were pinned down in homes or
shelters by the fierce fighting.
   Six Jesuit priests and two others killed along with them at a
Roman Catholic university were to be buried today after
international forensic experts examine the bodies.
   University officials said witnesses saw 30 men in army uniforms
enter the slain priests' residence just before the shooting began
Thursday. However, the U.S.-backed right-wing government denounced
the killings and said it would investigate.
   The murders were widely condemned in El Salvador and abroad, and
the U.S. ambassador offered protection to witnesses who come
forward.
   Dozens of religious workers, labor activists, academics and
political figures went into hiding after the slaughter of the
priests and the arrests Thursday of 12 Lutheran missionary workers.
The Lutherans, including four Americans, were released unharmed
Friday, the U.S. Embassy said.
   Union halls and a human rights office were broken into and
right-wing graffiti scrawled on the walls Friday, and a Roman
Catholic official said a right-wing supporter with a loudspeaker
yelled threats outside the residence of Monsignor Arturo Rivera
Damas, the archbishop of San Salvador.
   ``We have the justified fear that the assassinations are the
beginning of a series of actions against unions, labor groups and
politicians,'' said Fidel Chavez Mena, secretary-general of the
opposition Christian Democratic Party.
   Mena, whose centrist party governed the nation until its defeat
by President Alfredo Cristiani this year, blamed the ultra-right
for the killings.
   ``Whether they were part of the military or not, we don't
know,'' he said.
   Rivera Damas said at a Friday news conference that the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front rebels accepted his call for a
cease-fire but that the government has only said it would study the
proposal.
   Cristiani said in a television broadcast Friday night that the
fighting ``has been totally controlled'' in northern parts of the
capital and that ``only a few small centers'' of conflict remained
in San Salvador's eastern neighborhoods.
   The northern Meijicanos neighborhood was the scene of the only
heavy fighting in the capital area Friday. During that battle, a
British journalist, 44-year-old David Blundy, of the newspaper the
Sunday Correspondent, was fatally shot by a sniper.
   The shootings Thursday of Ignacio Ellacuria, rector of Jose
Simeon Canas Central American University near the capital,
vice-rector Ignacio Martin Baro, four other Jesuit priests, their
housekeeper and her 15-year-old daughter drew international
condemnation.
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker on Friday pressured the
Salvadoran government to quickly conduct an investigation and
launched an inquiry of his own, promising protection to witnesses.
   He said the killings were a ``blot on the image'' of El
Salvador's government that could only be erased by a full
investigation and punishment of the guilty.
   U.S. religious leaders blamed the slayings on right-wing forces
and called for a cutoff of U.S. aid to the Cristiani government.
   Democratic senators threatened to slash the aid unless Cristiani
ends the violence. The government has received $3.5 billion in aid
this decade.
   ``In an era of scarce foreign assistance, we need to be asking
what we are achieving for the dollars sent,'' Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass, told a Capitol Hill hearing Friday.
   Also Friday, Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., said Salvadoran national
guardsmen had detained a New Jersey teacher and peace activist in a
church along with other church workers since Thursday night.
   In his statement, Bradley said 53-year-old Teresa Fitzgibbon, of
Trenton, is part of a Lutheran Church group providing medical care
to refugees from the fighting.
   Jose Maria Tojeira, the head of the Jesuit order for Central
America, on Friday held a memorial Mass for the slain priests.
   ``History repeats itself. They have not died, they are alive
among the Salvadoran people,'' he said.
   After the killings, most of the faculty at the University of San
Salvador, heavily dominated by leftists, had ``withdrawn,'' said
vice-rector Herbert Barillas without elaboration.
   An annual report presented Friday at the United Nations accused
El Salvador's government of presiding over a ``resurgence of
torture'' this year and a crackdown on labor groups.
   Cristiani took office June 1 as the winning candidate of the
rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance founded by Roberto
D'Aubuisson, who has been linked to death squads blamed for killing
tens of thousands in the last decade.
  
</TEXT>
