<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Bridge     11-18 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Bridge,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bay Bridge Reopens but Authorities Expect Traffic Problems to Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FX2, FX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vital San Francisco-Oakland Bay
Bridge, whose ruptured span symbolized the power of the Oct. 17
earthquake, reopened to traffic exactly one month after the temblor.
   Six California Highway Patrol cruisers, sirens whining, and 13
private tow trucks, yellow lights flashing, led a parade on a 35
mph, 10-minute trip across the upper deck to San Francisco just
before midnight Friday.
   Westbound motorists who were kept a mile back from the bridge
until after it was officially reopened began driving across the
53-year-old structure for the first time since the 7.1-magnitude
quake struck Northern California.
   The temblor killed 66 people, including one motorist on the
bridge, and caused $7 billion in damages. It shook loose a 50-foot
section of the bridge. The loss of the Bay Bridge disrupted the
lives of residents who had to seek alternative routes to work, but
transportation officials warned the traffic nightmare would
continue Monday because of damaged bridge approaches and other
highway damage.
   Commuters who have been using mass transit, including cross-Bay
ferries and the underground Bay Area Rapid Transit system, were
urged to continue to do so.
   ``We had a traffic problem here even before the quake,'' said
Bob Halligan, a spokesman for the state Department of
Transportation. `Now people will have to decide if they want to sit
in their cars for hours on the Bay Bridge, or do they want to get
to work?''
   CHP officers led the way during the bridge opening to discourage
motorists from trying to set speed records on the empty span, said
Halligan.
   Drivers from two San Francisco towing companies were invited to
cross behind the highway patrol as thanks for having towed for free
dozens of cars that were abandoned on the bridge on the evening of
the quake.
</TEXT>
