<FIRST>r a PM-Presbyterians-Abortion     11-18 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presbyterians-Abortion,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Debate Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a bid to ease conflict among
Presbyterians on one of the country's most divisive issues,
advocates for and against legalized abortion vented their views at
a national conference.
   ``Church members must learn to listen to all perspectives, or
we're poorer as a community,'' said Carl Batzel, a pastor from
Susquehanna, Pa. ``In our denomination, there are too many times we
associate with only those of a like mind.''
   About 225 representatives from the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)
gathered Friday for the National Dialogue on Abortion Perspectives.
The church officially adopted a stand approving legalized abortion
in 1983, but each year since then its governing body has been asked
to reverse the policy.
   The church began setting up the conferences in 1987.
   During the opening session, Louise Lawson, associate pastor of a
Presbyterian church in Memphis, Tenn., said while she supports a
woman's right to an abortion, it should be used as ``a last
resort.''
   ``Anti-abortion advocates say pregnancy and childbearing always
represent God's will,'' but such a viewpoint does not consider the
free will of humans, Lawson said.
   Dr. Carolyn Gerster of Scottsdale, Ariz., who is active in the
National Right to Life Committee, said no issue since slavery has
divided the nation like abortion.
   ``I'm a feminist, but abortion involves the death of a
developing human,'' she said. ``Abortion is the death of a person.
... And that's not a matter of personal morality, but of public
morality.''
   The conference participants were chosen from regional governing
bodies of the church, called synods, from across the country. The
synods were asked to choose a delegation with a diversity of ideas
about abortion.
   The 3 million-member denomination created a task force on
problem pregnancies and abortion in 1988 and is working on a policy
statement on abortion.
</TEXT>
