<DOCNO> AP891118-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Boeing     11-18 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Proposes Three-Year Ban of Boeing Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Contract talks begin at 4:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing's government liaison office outside
Washington, D.C., has been suspended from signing new contracts
with the Pentagon because employees there obtained secret military
documents, Boeing said.
   The temporary suspension will last until authorities decide on
an Air Force recommendation to ban the office from doing business
with the military for up to three years, Boeing said Friday.
   Also Friday, a federal mediator scheduled negotiations in a
46-day strike by 57,000 Machinists that has virtually shut down
production lines at the aerospace giant.
   The Air Force suspension follows Boeing's guilty plea Monday in
U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va., to two felony charges of
obtaining classified military budget documents. The company agreed
to pay $5.2 million in fines and restitution.
   Boeing will argue against the proposed three-year suspension of
its 100-person office in Rosslyn, Va., saying it strengthened
internal controls after a federal investigation in 1986, according
to spokesman Paul Binder.
   The case against Boeing involved classified documents obtained
between 1979 and 1985 by Richard Lee Fowler, a senior marketing
analyst who was fired in 1986. Fowler is awaiting trial next month
on 39 counts of conspiracy and unauthorized conveyance.
   Some of the documents involved studies of the Strategic Defense
Initiative, the proposed missile defense system known popularly as
Star Wars.
   The suspension of just one Boeing office may mean the Air Force
doesn't want to seriously impair Boeing's military business, said
retired Rear Adm. Eugene J. Carroll, of the Center for Defense
Information in Washington, D.C., a military watchdog group.
   ``I've never heard of debarring just one office,'' Carroll said.
``They've found a way to sound as if they're taking serious action,
knowing there will be ways around the barrier.''
   Boeing did $4.2 billion of business with the government during
the first nine months of 1989, but reported it is losing money on
its defense-related contracts.
   The strike talks called for this afternoon by federal mediator
Doug Hammond are the third round since the walkout by members of
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers
began Oct. 4.
   Union negotiators rejected Boeing's last three-year offer, which
included annual wage increases of 4 percent, 3 percent and 3
percent, plus bonuses, cuts in mandatory overtime and increases in
retirement benefits.
   The union represents about 57,800 Boeing workers, including
43,000 in the Seattle area; 12,000 in Wichita, Kan.; 1,700 in
Portland, Ore., and a few hundred others at scattered sites in
California, Hawaii, Utah, Wyoming, Montana, North Dakota and
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
