<FIRST>r a PM-RefineryFire     11-18 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refinery Fire,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Erupts at Chevron Refinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hot crude oil leaking from a pump
caught fire at the Chevron refinery here, sending a ball of flame
70 feet into the air, officials said.
   No injuries or deaths were reported in the blaze that began
Friday night and no refinery workers were missing, Chevron
spokesman Rod Spackman said today.
   ``I wouldn't call it an explosion _ but it was a large pop that
kind of scared us,'' said El Segundo Fire Capt. Eric Moore, one of
the first firefighters to arrive after the 7:50 p.m. alarm.
   A petroleum distillation unit was damaged, but no damage figures
were immediately available, Spackman said.
   Firefighters poured streams of water onto the flames within the
plant, a few miles south of Los Angeles International Airport.
   The fire erupted in the distillation unit of the refinery's
single largest crude oil processing plant, officials said.
   A seal failed on a primary pump feeding crude oil into the unit,
Spackman said. Oil spilled from the pump onto the concrete pad
surrounding the unit and somehow ignited.
   Police closed a heavily used boulevard to traffic for several
hours until refinery and fire officials determined that the area
was safe, although thick clouds of smoke continued to billow into
the night.
   The smoke was not toxic or hazardous, Spackman said.
   The refinery processes about 250,000 barrels a day of crude oil,
producing gasoline, diesel and jet fuel.
</TEXT>
