<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Drugs     11-18 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Drugs,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Suspected Drug Traffickers Arrested in Soldiers' Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested 10 suspected drug
traffickers in the killings of seven soldiers and the head of a
federal police anti-narcotics group, the Attorney General's office
said.
   Its statement, released Friday, said the arrested men told
authorities their band put together heavily armed groups that
ambushed other drug traffickers, stole their drugs, and killed them.
   The office said the arrests were made Nov. 11, but it did not
say why they were not announced earlier.
   The soldiers' were shot to death Oct. 31 at a clandestine
airport in Santa Maria de Otaez, 600 miles northwest of Mexico City
in Durango state.
   A week later, Manuel Antonio Arias Palmeros, chief of a federal
judicial police unit, was killed and an agent with him seriously
wounded at a checkpoint outside Camargo, in the northwestern state
of Chihuahua.
   An investigation found Amado Levario Quiroz, a reputed drug
trafficker wanted in connection with other slayings, headed the
group that killed the eight, the attorney's office communique said.
   Levario Quiroz was killed Nov. 8, the day after the police chief
was slain, in a shootout with anti-narcotics police on a ranch near
Camargo.
   The attorney general's statement said the stolen drugs were
turned over to Levario Quiroz, who sold them in the United States.
   A Cessna airplane and six ranches belonging to him were seized,
the attorney general's statement said.
   The 10 suspects were taken for detention to Parral, Chihuahua.
Authorities are looking for more members of the band, the
attorney's office said.
</TEXT>
