<FIRST>r a PM-Shamir     11-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamir,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Prime Minister: No `Glasnost' Effect Yet in Middle East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir said Soviet arms keep pouring into neighboring Syria and he
urged U.S. officials to remain loyal to longtime alliances despite
changing superpower relations.
   ``We cannot see yet in our region any signs of glasnost,''
Shamir said at a Los Angeles World Affairs Council luncheon Friday.
   In his speech and a question-and-answer session Shamir was
intent on showing the democracy movement in Eastern Europe hasn't
diminished the United States' need for longtime allies.
   ``Loyal and firm allies are important to every country and under
all circumstances. This applies especially to a superpower and
especially because of the constantly changing circumstances. Israel
is such an ally of the United States and our alliance is as
steadfast as ever,'' he said.
   Israel remains threatened by countries ``committed to the
annihilation of Israel'' and ``backed by forces as large as those
of NATO,'' he said.
   Syria alone can field 700,000 troops, more than 4,000 tanks and
650 fighter planes against Israel, Shamir said.
   ``Now it is absorbing another huge shipment of Soviet arms,
including the most modern attack planes.''
   Asked about Israel's reaction to the opening of the Berlin Wall
and the possibility of the reunification of Germany, Shamir said,
``Of course all of us are moved by these great changes'' but
reunification ``is not now on the international agenda.''
   On other issues, Shamir reiterated proposals from a May peace
initiative that calls for Arab-Israeli peace talks preceded by
elections ``that will produce a democratically chosen
representative leadership of the Palestinians.''
   Once again he ruled out talks with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which he dismissed as a terrorist organization.
</TEXT>
