<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     11-18 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Told to Shoot Militiamen After Bloody Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops have been told to shoot to kill
members of a new Tamil militia after it attacked four eastern
police stations in battles that reportedly left 43 people dead, the
government said today.
   Eighteen guards were killed in the simultaneous attacks early
Friday in Ampara district, about 125 miles east of Colombo, the
state-run news agency Lankapuvath reported. Twenty-five members of
the militia were also reported killed.
   A government statement said the militia, known as the Tamil
National Army, has been declared an ``enemy of the country'' and
shoot-at-sight orders have been issued against its members.
   The militia is believed to have been set up by three former
rebel groups that now control the Northeastern Provincial Council,
the local government in the district.
   Although the militia was declared illegal, the government had
tolerated it. It was apparently set up to defend the provincial
council from attacks by rival Tamil groups, mainly the dominant
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   Fears of internecine fighting have been increasing with the
departure of Indian peacekeeping troops, who are to complete their
withdrawal from Sri Lanka by Dec. 31. Indian troops pulled out of
Ampara last month.
   In the first direct denouncement of the Tamil National Army and
its creators, Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne on Friday accused
the provincial council's chief minister Vartharaja Perumal of
creating the ``present situation.''
   ``We have information 13 unauthorized (militia) camps have been
set up in Ampara, trained by the Indian peacekeeping force and
armed by the chief minister,'' he told Parliament.
   Perumal ``has either gone mad or is being motivated to do
this,'' the minister said.
   ``If he cannot enforce law and order in the north and east, we
have people who can do this job,'' Wijeratne said.
   Indian officials in Colombo denied Indian troops had helped set
up the camps.
   Perumal, who heads the pro-Indian Eelam People's Revolutionary
Liberation Front, opposes withdrawal of Indian troops deployed in
northeastern Sri Lanka since July 30, 1987.
   The troops were dispatched under an Indian-Sri Lanka accord to
end a Tamil insurgency for a separate homeland. The agreement
provided limited autonomy to the Tamil minority.
   The provincial council also was set up under the accord, and
Perumal's group renounced separatism and joined mainstream
politics. The Tamil Tigers, however, reneged on the accord and
began attacking Indian soldiers.
   Days after the Indian troops withdrew from Ampara, the Tamil
Tigers attacked two Tamil National Army camps. At least 33 people
were killed.
   At least 10,000 Sri Lankans have been killed in the six-year-old
Tamil insurgency that stemmed from complaints of discrimination in
jobs and education by the Sinhalese majority.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese comprise 75 percent and control the government and the
military.
</TEXT>
