<HEAD>Collor de Mello Eyes Alliances for Runoff Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with later vote tallies, final
tally not expected until Sunday. Pickup 9th graf, `Both leftist...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fernando Collor de Mello, the
conservative front-runner in the presidential election, looked for
allies today to beat back a leftist challenge in a runoff next
month.
   Collor de Mello, of the center-right National Reconstruction
Party, appeared to have won first place with 26.9 percent of
Wednesday's first-round vote, according to partial tallies released
today by the government's Superior Electoral Court.
   Marxist Rep. Luis Inacio Lula da Silva ran second with 15.9
percent, trailed by leftist populist Leonel Brizola with 15.6
percent, according to the official count.
   The tallies were based on 76 percent of the votes cast. The
government expected to have a final tally officially counted by
Sunday.
   The top two vote-getters will face each other in a runoff on
Dec. 17. The country is holding its first free presidential
elections in 29 years.
   In its own tallies, Globo TV, the nation's largest network,
showed Brizola in second, a half million votes ahead of da Silva.
It said its independent count was based on 80 percent of the vote.
   Both leftist candidates claimed slim victories, but both also
pledged to support the other in a runoff.
   Collor de Mello reportedly was seeking support on the left to
shake his image as the representative of conservatives and the
wealthy.
   The 40-year-old former governor acknowledged making contacts
with the top advisers of Sen. Mario Covas, the candidate of the
left-center Brazilian Social Democracy Party.
   He was running a strong fourth with 12 percent of the vote,
according to the official tally.
   Covas did not dismiss the possibility of a coalition, saying,
``It is not up to me, but for the party to decide.''
   But he sounded skeptical. ``Everyone knows the PSDB is a
center-left party, and that should indicate certain things,'' he
said in the radio interview Friday.
   Also Friday, Roberto Della Manna, director of the powerful
Federation of Industries of Sao Paulo State, said in a published
interview that businessmen were solidly behind Collor de Mello.
   ``Lula and Brizola, especially Lula, would be a step backward
from modernization,'' Federation spokesman Luis Carlos Granadero
said.
   Ex-labor leader da Silva, of the radical-left Workers' Party,
appeared relaxed Friday in television interviews at his home in Sao
Bernardo do Campo, an industrial suburb of Sao Paulo.
   ``Our projections show us winning by 1 to 1.5 million votes,''
he said. ``We are now looking ahead to our strategy in the second
round.''
   However, Brizola's Labor Party released projections showing
Collor de Mello with 23 percent of the vote, Brizola with 18
percent, and da Silva with 17 percent.
   Brizola refused to speak to reporters Friday and remained inside
his home in Rio's beachfront neighborhood of Copacabana.
</TEXT>
