<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru   11-18 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0524,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Presents Credentials to New Lebanese Leader's Aide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 6th pvs, `Protocol dictates...' to UPDATE
with State Department confirmation. Pickup 7th pvs, `McCarthy, whose...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy today
presented his credentials to an aide to President Rene Mouawad,
underscoring Washington's backing for the new head of state.
   Also today, a small bomb exploded outside the home of Parliament
member Khatchig Babikian, causing damage but no casualties, police
said.
   It was the seventh attack on the property of a Christian
parliamentarian since the legislators defied Christian army Gen.
Michel Aoun and elected Mouawad this month as part of an Arab
League-sponsored peace plan for the civil war. None of the previous
blasts caused casualties.
   Sources close to Mouawad reported earlier today that McCarthy
drove to Syrian-policed north Lebanon and presented his credentials
to the new leader at his home in Ehden, a mountain resort in the
Cedars Mountains.
   However, it was later learned that McCarthy gave his credentials
to a Foreign Ministry official, Salah Staitiyeh, at Mouawad's home.
   Protocol dictates that the ministry receive ambassadors'
credentials first. Officials said that on Sunday morning McCarthy
will present his credentials to Mouawad in a formal ceremony.
Mouawad was elected Nov. 5.
   In Washington, a State Department official confirmed that
McCarthy had presented his credentials in Ehden but gave no further
details.
   McCarthy, whose embassy in Beirut closed last month after Aoun
supporters surrounded it, drove in a five-car convoy to Ehden from
Damascus, the Syrian capital, according to Mouawad aides, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   One source said Prime Minister-designate Salim Hoss, a Sunni
Moslem, and Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem,
will attend the ceremony Sunday, highlighting the three top
leaders' effort to work together.
   The United States has supported Mouawad's election on Nov. 5 in
a special Parliament session held in north Lebanon after Aoun's
threats to shell the chamber in Beirut. It also has welcomed
Parliament's approval of an Arab League-brokered plan for
Christian-Moslem coexistence after 14 years of civil war. The
accord shifts political power to the Moslem majority.
   Aoun has rejected Mouawad's election and the peace plan, mainly
because it did not include a fixed timetable for the evacuation of
40,000 Syrian troops from Lebanon. Aoun fought the Syrians, the
Moslems' main backers, for six months this year in battles that
killed thousands of people. He says the Syrians, who entered
Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate, are an
occupying force.
   Washington, a traditional backer of the Christians, has accused
Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, of complicating the peace march, and
urged him to recognize Mouawad.
   Mouawad's election ended a political vacuum that prevailed after
President Amin Gemayel's term expired Sept. 22, 1988, with
Parliament unable to elect a successor.
   Aoun emerged as head of a Christian Cabinet, while Hoss, who
served under Gemayel, led a Moslem government during that period.
Mouawad asked Hoss this week to form a government of national
reconciliation.
   McCarthy was assigned to Lebanon after Gemayel's term ended. He
refused to present his credentials to either Cabinet to avoid
consolidating the partition. At least five other ambassadors
accredited to Lebanon after September 1988 have not yet presented
their credentials.
   Washington withdrew McCarthy and all American personnel from the
embassy in Aukar, a Christian suburb, on Sept. 6 after supporters
of Aoun demonstrated at the compound to protest against U.S. policy.
</TEXT>
