<DOCNO> AP891118-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bulgaria 2ndLd-Writethru a0511 11-18 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0511,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>50,000 Attend Rally Of Independent Groups In Sofia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SOF3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with demonstration ending, new
quotes, moves up reference to police. Pickup 5th graf, `The 78-year-old...';
DELETES now-redundant 18th graf, `Hundreds of...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 people chanting ``We
want democracy!'' today staged the largest protest rally in the
history of Communist Bulgaria, one day after Parliament scrapped a
law forbidding dissent.
   The crowd carried hundreds of banners and sketches, some showing
longtime Communist leader Todor Zhivkov behind bars and with an
Adolf Hitler mustache painted over his face. The hard-line Zhivkov
was forced out last week.
   At the end of the three-hour demonstration, the crowd adopted
with a show of hands a declaration calling for an end to corruption
and police repression, the abandoning of censorship, the release of
political prisoners and guarantees for freedom of religion.
   The emotional gathering, organized by unofficial human rights
and ecological groups, was held on a vast downtown square in front
of the Aleksander Nevski Orthodox Cathedral in cold but sunny
weather.
   ``This is the return of democracy in Bulgaria, and a miracle we
have not seen for 45 years,'' Hristofor Sebec, a priest and a
member of the independent ecological group Ecoglasnost, said in an
interview.
   ``Bulgaria is going toward democracy, maybe even a multiparty
system. It will not be easy to reach that goal, but we will
manage,'' Petar Beron, a senior leader of Ecoglasnost, said in an
interview.
   Hundreds of uniformed policemen, some sitting in buses at a
distance, watched the crowd and listened to the fiery speeches
without intervening.
   The 78-year-old Zhivkov, who resigned Nov. 10 as Communist Party
chief, was replaced by former Foreign Minister Petar Mladenov.
   The 400-member Parliament on Friday voted unanimously by a show
of hands for Mladenov, 53, to replace Zhivkov as head of state also.
   The election and the pro-democracy demonstrations in Bulgaria
indicate the hard-line Communist state may be ready to embrace the
reform movement that has led to dramatic changes in the Soviet
Union, Poland, Hungary and East Germany.
   Mladenov said in a French television interview broadcast Friday
that he supports holding free elections.
   Government approval of today's rally was a gesture by the
Mladenov government to show his leadership is committed to some
change.
   Under Zhivkov's rule, only official rallies were allowed. On
Friday, the National Assembly eliminated a paragraph, Article 273,
from the penal code that had been used to suppress dissent. That
article provided punishment for anyone deemed to have slandered the
government or party.
   During Parliament's session Friday, the first-ever broadcast
live in postwar Bulgaria, deputies leveled harsh criticism at
Zhivkov.
   One legislator, Slavcho Trnski, said Zhivkov led a ``flamboyant
lifestyle,'' owning more than 30 residences.
   An officially organized rally Friday in support of Mladenov drew
10,000 people, after which about 500 people demonstrated
independently with many chanting for democracy and shouting ``Down
with the murderers!''
   In today's demonstration, independent and police estimates put
the crowd at more than 50,000. Some of the banners read, ``We are
the victims of repression,'' ``Christ is Our Savior,'' ``My family
has nothing to eat'' and ``Freedom and Democracy Now.''
   The crowd shouted, ``We want free elections!,'' ``We want a new
constitution!'' and ``Down with the Red Bourgeoisie!'' It called
out the name of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, popular in Bulgaria for his
economic and political reform program. Mladenov's name was also
occasionally heard.
   ``The single-party system is the symbol of totalitarian rule,''
said Radoy Ralin, Bulgaria's best known writer of satire and other
prose and one of 15 speakers, who addressed the crowd from the
church's steps.
   For such public comments Bulgarians would almost certainly have
ended up in jail only a few weeks ago, said one of the activists.
   ``Todor Zhivkov has left us with empty shops, corruption,
bureaucracy and despair,'' said Petko Simeonov, a prominent
sociologist and a leading member of Ecoglasnost.
   He demanded criminal investigation and court action against
Zhivkov, echoing demands already heard during Friday's official
rally in downtown Sofia.
   The crowd responded by shouting ``Zhivkov to court!'' and ``Down
with Zhivkov and his aides!''
   Simeonov also called for ``immediate free election and freedom
of speech'' to the cheers of the crowd, who chanted ``Izbori,
izbori!'' (elections, elections).
   On Friday, Mladenov vowed to implement reforms. He told
Parliament that the command and bureaucratic system are beginning
to shake'' and fresh air of changes has entered the political
atmosphere.''
   The National Assembly adopted several government changes that
cleared out some hard-line Zhivkov supporters and restructured some
ministries to focus greater attention on the flagging economy and
the environment _ an issue of considerable popular concern.
</TEXT>
