<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EGermany-StayingPut Bjt   11-18 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Staying Put, Bjt,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>For One East Berliner, Security Beats the Lure of the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABNER KATZMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are plenty of want ads for plumbers in
the West Berlin papers, but being on the maintenance crew at the
House of Ministries in East Berlin is still the best guarantee of
the good life for Uwe Doering.
   ``When we saw all the beautiful things in the West, they were
very alluring,'' his girlfriend, Gabi Lamper, said Thursday. ``But
that doesn't mean we should leave home.''
   The couple and their 13-month-old son, Tom, were among the 99
percent of East German visitors to the West who have gawked at the
West German economic miracle in the past week and then returned
home.
   While the new travel freedom and political reforms in East
Germany dazzle the couple, their priorities are home, family and
the security of staying put.
   For the 26-year-old plumber, who joined the Communist Party as
an idealistic teen-ager, politics have taken a back seat to
economic considerations.
   Despite the cascade of changes in their country and their visit
to West Berlin one week ago, the big event in their lives is next
week's move into a new three-bedroom apartment.
   For both of them, the new apartment is a symbol of what is right
with East Germany _ a social system that Doering trusts to take
care of him and his family with guaranteed jobs and housing.
   ``People in West Berlin are jobless, on the dole,'' said
Doering, sprawled on a sofa and sipping a beer.
   ``Even though they get money, I wouldn't want my family to live
in a hotel, or a hole in the wall, if I can have a three-bedroom
apartment here and a job.''
   The couple spoke through an intepreter to The Associated Press
at their one-bedroom apartment in Prenzlauerberg, a working-class
section of East Berlin.
   Doering saved all his pay from three years' army service, which
enabled them to buy the television, stereo and the furniture that
fills half their 12-by-12 foot living room.
   ``I could afford the television because I sold my motorcycle,''
Doering joked. ``Three people don't fit on a motorbike.''
   Last year, Doering bought a 1968 East German-made Trabant, which
both he and Ms. Lamper drive.
   Now the house is too small, with Tom's playpen and toys. The
baby sleeps in a crib at the foot of his parents' bed in their
cramped 5-by-12 foot bedroom.
   Other signs of prosperity jammed into their third-floor walk-up
apartment include a washing machine, oversized refrigerator, food
processer and electric bread slicer.
   They count themselves lucky that they were able to get a new
apartment allocation from the government in just a year. Doering
remembers when life was different.
   ``I came to Berlin in 1970 with my family,'' he said with a
grimace. ``At that time, we were four people living in a one-room
apartment. It was a terrible time.''
   He and Ms. Lamper openly admit to playing along with the
Communist system for their benefit.
   For example, the new apartment might have taken three years to
get if Doering had not kept his own one-bedroom apartment when he
moved into what was his girlfriend's place three years ago.
   The combination of two one-person apartments to trade, and their
new child to consider, was enough to swing the odds in their favor.
   Now Ms. Lamper is looking for a day-care center, or a creche,
for Tom. Until she finds one, ``I get 700 marks ($35) a month for
doing nothing,'' she said.
   ``It's easier to get a creche when you're an unmarried mother,''
she said. ``In that way the GDR (German Democratic Republic) is
really a socialist state. They take care of unmarried mothers.''
   Ms. Lamper banks her money each month, and the family lives on
Doering's pay, which comes to about 1,100 marks a month, worth
about $60 at the unofficial exchange rate.
   Their apartment costs 47 marks a month, the equivalent of about
$2.50, and utilities run 20 marks a month.
   They spend about 20 marks a day on food and rarely see shortages
of meat and vegetables anymore.
   Doering said he joined the Communist Party at 18 out of a sense
of duty after being impressed by a rehabilitation plan for criminal
offenders in a factory where he worked.
   ``My mind has changed completely over the past years,'' he said.
``The confidence they have broken has to be rebuilt. The economy
has to be right, and it doesn't matter under which party.''
   Freedom to travel was ``the first step in the right direction,''
Doering said. ``Now, if a few more things change, life could be
really fine.''
</TEXT>
