<FIRST>r i AM-China-Socialism     11-18 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Socialism,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Steps Up Calls to Perfect Socialism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As political upheavals in Eastern Europe
continue, China is stepping up calls to preserve its own
conservative brand of socialism.
   Prominent editorials in newspapers have urged the ``perfection''
of socialism by rejecting political pluralism and denouncing the
most salient principle of capitalism: private ownership.
   Hungary has disbanded its Communist Party; East Germany, Poland
and Bulgaria have installed new reform-minded leaderships;
Czechoslovakia has replaced hard-liners in the Politburo with
moderates. But China is proving to be doctrinaire, stressing that
the conservative socialist path is best.
   ``Economic reform must on no account take the road of private
ownership, and the political reform must on no account take the
road leading to a multi-party or diversified political system,''
said the People's Daily, the main publication of China's Communist
Party.
   ``The ongoing policies of reform and opening further to the
outside world must stick to the socialist orientation,'' said the
commentary, written by Beijing University's president, Wu Shuqing,
and printed Friday.
   ``If the reform deviates from the socialist orientation and
follows the mode set by foreign hostile forces and those engaged in
advocating bourgeois liberalism (Western ideals), ... the socialist
cause and the great achievements China has obtained over the past
40 years will be destroyed in a moment,'' Wu wrote.
   Wu was installed as head of China's most prestigious university
in August, following a pro-democracy movement led by students, many
from Beijing University.
   China's brush with the call for democratic reforms was brutally
put down by the Chinese army in June in a crackdown which left
hundreds, and possibly thousands, of civilians dead.
   Since then, the government has intensified its criticism of the
West's liberal influences and exhorted Chinese to unite under the
party.
   Deng's early reforms included reviving the family farm and
allowing farmers to sell crops above state quotas for a profit and
to sometimes branch into private business.
   But at a time when democratic and capitalistic principles are
gaining the upper hand in traditionally hard-line Eastern Europe,
private ownership has come under fire in China as undermining the
socialist state.
   ``Privatization of state-owned assets under China's current
circumstances will inevitably create bureaucratic capitalism in the
country,'' a commentary in the journal Economic Research said.
   ``Instead of saving the country, bureaucratic capitalism can
only drive the masses of the Chinese people into an abyss of
misery,'' said the commentary, reprinted Saturday in the official
China Daily.
   ``In all human history, there has been only one case in which a
society of public ownership changed into a private one. And that
happened when the primitive communist society evolved into a slave
society,'' the Economic Research commentary said.
   ``If the public assets of today's China were privatized in a
short period of time, as hoped for by advocates, power could mean
greater opportunities for plundering public assets,'' it said.
   Wu, in his commentary, noted that proponents maintain that
private ownership fosters efficiency, while under public ownership
few concern themselves with economic development.
   But, he said, ``China and many other countries which have taken
the road of public ownership have developed their economies much
more quickly than many of the countries which have private
ownership systems since the second World War.''
   All shortcomings of public ownership system can be rectified
through reform, he said.
</TEXT>
