<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-USSummit     11-18 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-US Summit,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says Summit Expected to Further Economic Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said today
he expected next month's U.S.-Soviet summit to lay the groundwork
for greater economic cooperation between the superpowers.
   Shevardnadze said he believed President Bush would seek ``a more
basic, deeper understanding of what is happening in the Soviet
economy'' when he meets with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
near Malta in the Mediterranean.
   Bush and U.S. business leaders want to be ``convinced of the
stability of Soviet society ... and on the basis of such a
conviction, of such a conception, to build large-scale economic
cooperation,'' Shevardnadze said.
   The Dec. 2-3 shipboard summit has no set agenda, and
Shevardnadze said no proposed treaties were being prepared for the
summit and no signing of agreements was expected. But ``there could
definitely be major agreements, I don't rule that out,''
Shevardnadze said.
   Along with giving Bush his views on the Soviet economy,
Gorbachev also wants to discuss some of the shortcomings of the
U.S. economy, particularly the question of massive loans it is owed
by Third World countries.
   ``That is question No. 1, I would say, both for the United
States and for the Third World,'' Shevardnadze said. ``This is one
of the questions which demand serious attention.''
   Soviet and U.S. officials have ruled out the idea of the United
States offering aid to the Soviet Union as it has to Eastern
European countries to encourage reforms. However, Soviets have
complained that America could offer more incentive to its
businessmen to invest in the Soviet economy.
   In an example of the kind of breaks the Soviets are looking for,
U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said Thursday the expected
quick easing of Soviet emigration restrictions will open up the
Soviet Union for most-favored-nation trade status with the United
States.
   Shevardnadze said the two leaders would also discuss a wide
range of issues, including recent changes in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
