<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Bomb 2ndLd-Writethru   11-18 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bomb, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0533,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede COLCHESTER</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three British Soldiers Killed in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with three British soldiers killed
in Northern Ireland. Pickup 6th pvs, `The sergeant...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three British soldiers were
killed in a bomb explosion in Northern Ireland today, and a British
army sergeant and his wife were wounded in a car bombing in eastern
England, police said.
   The three soldiers were on patrol in a Land-Rover near
Mayobridge, a rural area six miles from the border with the Irish
Republic, when the bomb exploded, the Royal Ulster Constabulary
said. Unconfirmed reports said a fourth soldier was seriously
injured, but no other details were immediately available.
   The off-duty sergeant suffered serious leg injuries and his wife
received less serious, unspecified injuries when a car bomb
exploded at the British army's headquarters in eastern England,
Essex police said.
   No group claimed responsibility for either attack. But suspicion
fell on the Irish Republican Army, which has often targeted the
security forces in its campaign to end British rule in Northern
Ireland and unite the mainly Protestant province with the
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   Police and Home Office Secretary David Waddington blamed the IRA
for the Colchester attack. The explosion there came less than 24
hours after Defense Secretary Tom King visited the Royal Anglian
Regiment at the Goojerat Barracks in the town, which is 50 miles
northeast of London. King was Northern Ireland secretary until a
Cabinet reshuffle in July.
   The sergeant and his wife were taken to Colchester General
Hospital. A Ministry of Defense spokesman, speaking anonymously,
said the sergeant suffered very serious leg wounds.
   An army spokesman, also speaking anonymously in keeping with
British custom, said the explosion involved a car in the married
quarters at the barracks and touched off a fire.
   Kim Bryan, son of the manager of the local pub, told Independent
Radio News that his mother ran up the road after hearing the
explosion and saw the car on fire and two people inside. They were
pulled out by others who rushed to the scene.
   Police and the army sealed off part of the town, the
third-largest garrison town in Britain, and with its Roman links,
the oldest. Homes near the scene of the blast were evacuated as
bomb squad officers conducted an investigation.
   About 4,500 troops are based at Colchester, which is army
headquarters for the 11-county eastern district and home of the
19th Infantry Brigade. Many civilians in the town are employed by
the military.
   The Ministry of Defense stepped up security at barracks and
military establishments across Britain following the IRA bombing
Sept. 22 at the Royal Marines Music School in Deal, which killed 11
men.
   The IRA also has claimed responsibility for a spate of bomb and
gun attacks on British servicemen and their families stationed in
West Germany. A soldier's wife was killed this summer and a
6-month-old girl died last month with her father, a Royal Air Force
corporal, in an IRA car bombing.
</TEXT>
