<FIRST>u a PM-TrailerFire 1stLd-Writethru a0513 11-18 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trailer Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trailer Fire In Rural Area Kills Nine; Two Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with eight of nine are children; quotes,
other detail. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAXTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early morning blaze gutted a trailer in a
rural area today, killing a mother, her five children and three
other children, authorities said.
   Two adults escaped, one of them the mother of three of the
children who had to be restrained from re-entering the blazing
trailer, neighbors and officials said.
   ``She was hollering, `My babies! My babies!' She wanted to go
back in and get them,'' said Angie Locklear, who lives across the
road from the trailer.
   The fire erupted about 4 a.m. on one of the first cold nights of
the season and quickly engulfed a single trailer sitting on a
wooded lot off a rural dirt road, said Robeson County sheriff's
dispatcher Gene Lambert.
   The cause of the fire was under investigation.
   Locklear said she heard some sort of explosion and first thought
it was a gunshot, but ``when I looked out, all I could see were
flames.''
   She said a woman and a man ran out of trailer. When the woman
tried to return to rescue her children, the man restrained her.
   Neighbors said the woman was a relative of Lois Ann Hunt, 32,
the only victim who was immediately identified.
   Mrs. Hunt's five children ranged in age from 1{ to 12 years old,
while the visiting youngsters included an infant and a sixth- or
seventh-grader, neighbors said.
   Fire officials remained on the scene late this morning, sifting
through the cinders of the mobile home.
   The two survivors were treated for minor burns and injuries
suffered in the blaze and released, said Scotland Memorial Hospital
emergency room Dr. Lloyd McCaskill.
</TEXT>
