<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-TheModel     11-18 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-The Model,0820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swedish Mix of Capitalism and Socialism Studied by East Europeans</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1930s, Sweden's mix of
capitalism and socialism became a model for reformers seeking to
protect the worker in the profit-hungry industrial West.
   Now, Eastern Europeans breaking free of Marxist economics and
stifling central planning are studying the Scandinavian way of
doing things.
   A parade of visitors has marched through Scandinavia from
Hungary, Poland, the Baltic republics and the Soviet Union itself,
and the questions they ask highlight how difficult their transition
will be to economic freedom.
   ``The Swedish model has interested us for a long time, now more
than ever, both on a practical and theoretical level,'' said
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze of the Soviet Union in a
written reply to questions from a Swedish newspaper last week.
   Reszo Nyers, Hungarian Socialist Party leader and architect of
Hungary's economic reforms, said in Stockholm there is ``a lot for
us to pay attention to concerning the Swedish model, such as how
Sweden combines a market economy and the state at the same time
takes responsibility for social solutions.''
   Bankers, company managers, government leaders and economic
planners are among those coming here. Often they seek investment
and joint ventures. More often, they just want advice on how to
cope and compete in a free market.
   The Swedish model, or what was called 50 years ago ``the middle
way,'' refers to the merging of a vigorous capitalist-based private
industry with all-embracing egalitarian welfare programs, financed
by taxes designed to reduce the gap between rich and poor.
   In the drive to strip the Communist party of total power, East
bloc visitors show interest in Sweden's muscular labor unions and
its strong municipalities, which take the bulk of tax revenues and
handle most public services.
   Sweden's government-run retraining program is being keenly
studied by Poland, which faces a grim prospect of massive
unemployment, according to a Swedish government official involved
in the contacts. He was interviewed on condition he was not
identified.
   Poland has been warned by the International Monetary Fund that
economic revitalization could initially mean one of every three
Polish workers without a job. ``They know this is not a good way to
start on the road to democracy,'' this official said.
   Sweden restructured its economy in the 1970s, phasing out
unprofitable shipbuilding and other heavy industries while giving
top priority to retraining workers and keeping employment levels
high.
   Today, the Swedish inflation rate is higher than in most of
Europe, above 6 percent, but unemployment is an enviable 1.5
percent.
   Though Sweden's Social Democrats are credited with creating the
model Welfare State, all postwar Scandinavian countries embrace it.
   Finland and Sweden, admired as prosperous and efficient, have
the additional appeal of being neutral, while Norway and Denmark
belong to the NATO military alliance.
   East bloc economic leaders have been traveling elsewhere in
Western Europe, seeking capitalistic wisdom and an infusion of aid.
   ``It's not only us,'' said the Swedish official. ``But it's hard
for a Pole to turn to West Germany, for political and historical
reasons,'' he said.
   Traffic has been heaviest to Finland, which has one of the
fastest growing economies in Europe this decade. Helsinki has a
friendship treaty with the Soviet Union and a long history of
economic links. The Finns also are culturally and linguistically
related to Estonians.
   The other Scandinavian countries have large East European
refugee populations.
   On a visit to Finland last month, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
of the Soviet Union suggested to Finnish industrialists that they
set up a management training program for Soviet factory directors.
   Similar projects are being arranged privately. The Danish
Chamber of Commerce has invited 30 company directors from Estonia,
Latvia and Lithuania to attend management courses in Copenhagen
next spring.
   ``They are well educated people, as engineers and technicians.
But they don't know anything about consumer or industrial
marketing, exhibiting, transportation, appointing agents,'' said
Vagn Jensen, deputy director of the Chamber of Commerce.
   The Baltic states also want to step up business contacts in
Scandinavia for hard-cash reasons: under Soviet law, they are
allowed to use export income in the currencies of neighboring
countries to buy imports.
   So far, the Scandinavians have been wary of investing in the
shaky Eastern economies. Businessmen demand guarantees that their
governments have been unwilling to give.
   But attitudes are changing, says Tor Oestboe, senior vice
president of the Export Finance A@S in Oslo, which is owned by
Norway's commercial banks.
   ``We are working on a new finance agreement with the Eastern
Bloc countries that would be a big step forward. First we are
working it out with the Soviet Union and the other East Bloc
countries will come later,'' he said.
</TEXT>
