<FIRST>u a PM-SuspectSlain 2ndLd-Writethru a0509 11-18 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suspect Slain, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0509,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sought in DEA Slaying, One of `10 Most Wanted,' Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that man found in car, sted on
street, adds details of killing, comments from U.S. attorney and FBI at
a news conference. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A low-level mobster suspected of killing a
federal drug agent in February was shot to death, probably on
orders from mob bosses angry about the scrutiny the agent's murder
brought them, authorities said today.
   Constabile ``Gus'' Farace was shot Friday night as he sat in a
car _ the same manner in which he allegedly killed Everett Hatcher,
a special agent with the Drug Enforcement Administration, who was
posing as a drug buyer.
   Hatcher's death Feb. 28 sparked a nationwide manhunt that
involved up to 100 federal agents working seven days a week, said
U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney. Farace was also to be featured Sunday
as the country's ``No. 1 fugitive'' on the Fox network television
show ``America's Most Wanted.''
   ``It's reasonable to assume all of that pressure could have
resulted in last night's shooting,'' Maloney said.
   ``A rational and prudent person would obviously believe that
this is probably a mob hit,'' said Robert Stutman, head of the
DEA's New York office. ``The investigation is continuing; I can't
say that for sure.''
   Hatcher, 46, was shot to death in February on Staten Island
after he went to meet Farace to set up a cocaine deal, police said.
He was shot four times in the head and upper body as he sat behind
the wheel of his car.
   Hatcher had been trying to infiltrate a cocaine ring run by the
mob, authorities said.
   On Friday, Farace, 29, was sitting in the front passenger seat
of a car parked on a Brooklyn street when a blue van pulled up
alongside him about 11 p.m. Seven to nine shots were fired into the
car, Maloney said at a news conference this morning.
   Farace was found dead slumped in his seat.
   The driver, Joseph Sclafani, who had been hit in the chest,
managed to get out of the car and fire a few shots from his
.38-caliber handgun at the fleeing van, he said.
   Sclafani, in his 20s, was found a few feet from the car and
taken to Coney Island Hospital, where he was in critical condition.
   Maloney described Farace as a ``young punk'' associated with the
Bonanno and Colombo crime families.
   ``I think it's reasonable to assume organized crime figures were
aware of the intensity of the investigation,'' Maloney said. ``I
assume that people higher up (in the Mafia) were as interested in
finding him as we were.''
   ``Mob justice isn't always swift, but it's always deadly, and
this may be an example of deadly mob justice,'' James Fox, head of
the New York FBI office, said at the news conference.
   Hatcher was a 12-year veteran of the DEA in New York and its
first agent killed here since 1972.
   His death prompted one of the largest manhunts in recent years
and rewards totaling $270,000 were offered, including $250,000 from
the federal government.
   ``I have never been involved with anything as intense or
emotional as this,'' Stutman said today. ``There were times we were
within two hours of him and he disappeared.''
   Farace was paroled in June 1988 after serving eight years for a
kidnap-murder.
</TEXT>
