<FIRST>r i AM-Havel     11-18 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Havel,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Dissident Given Visa to Accept Award in Sweden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav Havel,
that country's leading dissident, has received an exit visa so he
can come to Stockholm to accept a human rights award, officials
said Saturday.
   Sweden's foreign minister, Sten Andersson, had planned to go to
Prague, Czechoslovakia, on Thursday to present the $15,500 Olof
Palme prize to Havel because it was not expected the government
would allow Havel to leave the country.
   ``We will leave it to Havel to decide whether he prefers to come
here or receive the prize in Prague,'' Foreign Ministry spokeswoman
Helena Boutrup told The Associated Press.
   The Czechoslovak Embassy said Havel received his exit visa
Friday.
   The Olof Palme memorial prize, named for the Swedish prime
minister murdered in 1986, is awarded to champions of human rights
and peace.
   Havel is a member of the Charter 77 human rights group and has
been jailed in Czechoslovakia various times for his stance against
the Communist government.
