<FIRST>r i AM-India-Punjab     11-18 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Kill Six People in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded in downtown Amritsar
on Saturday, killing at least six people, police said.
   The explosions, in two shopping centers, injured more than 60
people, said hospital sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blasts, which occurred
around 5.30 p.m. in this city in Punjab state.
   Similar explosions in June 1988 in Amritsar were blamed on Sikh
militants campaigning for an independent homeland in Punjab.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are a
slight majority in Punjab, where militants have been leading a
violent campaign since 1982 for a separate homeland. They allege
they are discriminated against by India's Hindu majority.
   At least 1,600 deaths have been blamed on Sikh militants in
Punjab this year.
