<FIRST>u a PM-WalesaVisit 2ndLd-Writethru a0494 11-18 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walesa Visit, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0494,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Poles Greet Walesa, Who Says He's Not There with Hat in Hand</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with morning meeting, picking up
3rd graf pvs, `He is...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa came to the nation's biggest
Polish-American community to seek financial help for Poland's
struggling economy, but he said today he is not here with his ``hat
held out.''
   ``I have come here to prove that our system does not beg ... but
appeals to you as teachers, to help us to step onto the right path
of development,'' Walesa said at a morning meeting with officials
of the Polish American Congress.
   ``We want to learn from you how to develop a country, how to
move it from a system that failed to one that works.''
   The Nobel prize-winning labor leader said he is not seeking
direct financial aid from U.S. politicians or businessmen,
emphasizing that Poland wants to concentrate on joint ventures.
   ``We shouldn't go around with our hat held out,'' Walesa said,
speaking through an interpreter.
   Although business was on his mind, Walesa's first moments in
Chicago after his arrival late Friday were warmed by a welcome in
the tradition of his homeland.
   He was given a loaf of bread, a bag of salt and a bouquet of
flowers by about 100 people who greeted him at a neighborhood
monument to the Solidarity movement he helped found.
   ``He is a symbol to us. We call him `harnash,''' said Stanley
Dzierzega, vice president of the Polish Highlanders Alliance of
America. ``It means leader, and he is our leader, a symbol of
freedom.''
   Walesa arrived at Midway Airport late Friday from New York on
the latest leg of a trip intended to encourage U.S. investment in
Poland's faltering economy. The trip included an emotional meeting
with President Bush and a speech before an enthusiastic joint
session of Congress in which Walesa, an electrician, said
investment from the West is needed to ensure the success of
political reforms in his country.
   Chicago, with 800,000 residents of Polish descent, is the
biggest Polish community outside Warsaw, and Walesa's one-day visit
was expected to draw large crowds. The agenda consists largely of
meetings with business and labor leaders.
   At Friday night's ceremony in the city's heavily Polish
southwest side, the traditional gifts of welcome were presented by
members of the Highlanders, who work to preserve Polish culture in
the United States.
   ``He said he was happy to see us here in America,'' Dzierzega
said.
   Members of the group, dressed in embroidered folk shirts and
blouses and lamb's wool vests, also gave Walesa an ax, which they
said was a Polish symbol of freedom.
   Despite wind-whipped snow and sub-freezing temperatures, about
100 people greeted him at the stone memorial to Solidarity, and a
score of others were turned away by security guards.
   ``I am Polish. I was a union member, and what I like about the
guy is he had guts,'' Frank Mrozowski said as the motorcade left.
``He said he was going to organize a union, and that was it.''
   Walesa departs tonight for Philadelphia. He was scheduled to
attend Mass Sunday at a Polish shrine in Doylestown, a suburb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
