<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     11-18 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Returns to Lebanon, Tells Aoun to Behave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KHODOR TALEB</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EHDEN, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy, pulled from
Lebanon 73 days ago under pressure from supporters of Christian
Gen. Michel Aoun, returned Saturday and urged the rebellious Aoun
to ``fall in line behind civilian authority.''
   McCarthy drove to Ehden in Syrian-controlled north Lebanon to
present his credentials to a foreign ministry official at the home
of President Rene Mouawad. A Beirut newspaper reported that the
United States is considering reopening its mission in Lebanon but
moving it out of the region controlled by Aoun.
   The presenting of credentials underscored U.S. backing for the
new head of state, whom Aoun opposes, and intensified the general's
political isolation.
   Earlier, a small bomb exploded outside the home of Armenian
parliamentary deputy Khatchig Babikian in Christian east Beirut,
causing damage but no casualties, police reported.
   It was the seventh attack on a Christian parliamentarian since
legislators defied Aoun and elected Mouawad president on Nov. 5 to
oversee implementation of an Arab League-sponsored peace plan to
end 14 years of civil war.
   The accord was reached by the legislators in 23 days of talks in
the Saudi Arabian resort of Taif.
   Mccarthy and his bodyguards arrived in Ehden in a five-car
convoy. Security around Mouawad's two-story stone mansion was tight.
   ``I wanted to bring the greetings of President Bush to President
Mouawad,'' McCarthy told reporters.
   ``My country was very, very pleased to see the developments that
took place in Taif, to see the election of a new president here, to
see that the situation, that had been ambigious in terms of
legality, has now totally cleared,'' he added. ``You have a
president. That's a wonderful thing.''
   In remarks aimed at Aoun, McCarthy said, ``Lebanon has a long
tradition of constitutional democracy. In that tradition, as far as
I know, military officers have always followed the civilian
authority.''
   The envoy said he assumed that Aoun, ``like the good soldier he
is ... will very soon fall in line behind civilian authority. I
certainly hope so.''
   McCarthy said the Bush administration ``has a good deal of
respect for Gen. Aoun'' and agreed with his goals. ``It was really
the means he was using that we quarreled with.''
   Aoun, who seeks to force the 40,000 Syrian soldiers out of
Lebanon, fought them for six months in fierce artillery battles
that killed more than 900 people and wounded nearly 3,000. The
fighting ended Sept. 22 with an Arab League-brokered cease-fire.
   The general opposed the Taif accord because it did not include a
guarantee for the withdrawal of the Syrians, who were deployed in
1976 under an Arab League mandate to quell civil war fighting. Aoun
said they defied that mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   Salah Staitiyeh, head of the Foreign Ministry's political
affairs department, said McCarthy presented a copy of his
credentials to him at 1:45 p.m.
   The ambassador will formally present his credentials to Mouawad
on Sunday, officials reported.
   McCarthy held a 30-minute meeting with Mouawad. Reporters were
not allowed in, but photographers were given 10 minutes to take
pictures.
   The two men later drove together in Mouawad's bulletproof
Mercedes to the neighboring town of Zghorta away for a lunch given
by former President Suleiman Franjieh.
   Lebanese soldiers in armored personnel carriers guarded the
mountain road between Ehden and Zghorta. Mouawad and McCarthy
returned to Ehden several hours later and talked for 90 minutes. No
statement was issued.
   Beirut's leftist As-Safir newspaper reported from Washington
that the United States was ``seriously considering reopening its
embassy in Lebanon, but outside the Christian enclave'' controlled
by Aoun.
   The daily quoted unnamed American sources as saying McCarthy
would discuss with Mouawad the idea of moving the embassy to the
Syrian-policed north.
   McCarthy and other U.S. diplomats evacuated the embassy in
Christian east Beirut on Sept. 6 after Aoun loyalists besieged it.
   Asked whether the embassy would reopen, McCarthy said: ``We'll
return as soon as our security can be guaranteed and as soon as
we're certain we can have contacts with all the different political
leaders in Lebanon.''
</TEXT>
