<FIRST>u w AM-CatastrophicCoverage     11-18 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Coverage,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeal of Medicare Expansion One Step Away</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress-Pay Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is a step away from abolishing the
year-old Medicare program designed to protect retirees against
being bankrupted by the costs of a catastrophic illness.
   Senate negotiators reluctantly agreed Saturday morning to a
House demand that catastrophic coverage be repealed. However, a
Republican senator who led the battle to scale back the program
vowed to use whatever tactic is available in the closing days of
this year's session to prevent repeal.
   ``Every elderly group in America ... has come out loud and clear
that they do not want repeal,'' Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said
after hearing of the negotiators' action. He indicated he will
filibuster in an effort to keep part of the program alive.
   Repeal, he said, would be an incredible injustice. ``Starting in
January, people now in nursing facilities will be ejected ... after
20 days,'' McCain said as an example of what many of the nation's
32 million retirees will be losing by repeal.
   Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas also urged the Senate to
fight repeal.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee and a vocal opponent of repeal, said ``there was a lot of
deep disappointment (in his committee) starting with me'' because
of the House negotiators' refusal to back away from their
insistence on repeal.
   Despite McCain's filibuster threat, repeal is considered nearly
certain. That is because if the repeal bill is rejected, it is
quite likely this late in the congressional year that the existing
law would remain on the books. Few members of either house want
that.
   The House already has voted once for repeal by a lopsided
margin. Although the Bush administration has said it would prefer
to keep the program intact, congressional say they would expect
President Bush to sign a repeal bill.
   The catastrophic health coverage was enacted with heavy
bipartisan support last year as the largest expansion ever of the
Medicare program.
   But catastrophic protection quickly ran into a barrage of
complaints from some retirees. Many complained that they didn't
need the new federal protection because they already have
catastrophic coverage through a private plan or a retirement plan.
   Many higher-income retirees were outspoken against the program
because they were hit with having to pay an income surtax of up to
$800 a year to finance most of the program. They argued that such a
health benefit should be paid for by all taxpayers _ not just
middle- and upper-income retirees.
   The mail was so heavy against the program that the House had no
trouble voting to repeal, over objections of its Democratic
leadership. The Senate thwarted the repeal effort at first,
accepting instead a scaling back sponsored by McCain.
   The McCain amendment would repeal the surtax and coverage for
drugs and doctors' fees but retain coverage for hospital bills.
Those benefits and some relatively minor ones, including hospice
care and once-a-year mammograms, would be financed by continuing
and increasing the flat $4 monthly premium paid by most retirees.
   Even if the law is wiped off the books, catastrophic protection
for many of the nation's poorest retirees would continue being
provided through the federal-state Medicaid program.
   The catastrophic program began providing coverage for hospital
bills late Jan. 1. In the absence of repeal, protection for
doctors' fees and some prescription drugs would begin next Jan. 1.
   Under the program, a retiree could have an unlimited hospital
stay and pay no more than $560 a year. Next year, a person's
out-of-pocket payments for doctors' bills would be limited to
$1,370 a year.
</TEXT>
