<FIRST>u i AM-Ethiopia 1stLd-Writethru   11-18 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0538,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Rebels Claim New Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with government comment. Pickup
4th graf `If true...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopian rebels say they have captured a
small town 85 miles north of the capital of Addis Ababa and halted
a government counterattack.
   In a clandestine radio broadcast monitored in Nairobi late
Friday, the Tigre People's Liberation Front said its fighters took
the town of Meranya Thursday and repulsed troops counterattacking
southward from Desse, the capital of Wollo Province.
   The rebel claims could not be independently verified. The
government, in its own communique Friday, made no mention of
fighting around Meranya.
   However, the official Ethiopian news agency said government
forces ``repulsed recently an offensive by the TPLF against Desse
from all fronts.''
   The government has rarely commented on the Tigrean offensive,
which began in late August when the insurgents pushed southward out
of Tigre into Wollo and neighboring Gonder provinces.
   If true, the front's claim means its forces have moved southward
past Desse, a heavily armed government garrison that they were
unable to capture in heavy fighting last month. Desse controls a
vital junction on the road from Addis Ababa to Assab, one of only
two Ethiopian ports on the Red Sea.
   The government and the rebel front met in Rome last week for the
first time in their 14-year-old conflict, but neither side has
commented on what were described as preliminary peace talks.
   The government is scheduled to meet in Nairobi on Monday with
representatives of another major insurgency, the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front.
   The Eritreans have been fighting since 1961 for secession.
   The Tigreans say they want to replace Ethiopia's Marxist regime
with a democratic government, although the Tigrean rebel leadership
itself is considered Marxist.
</TEXT>
