<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-18 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Claims to Defeat New Tamil Militia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops backed by cannons
and shoot-to-kill orders claimed Saturday to have defeated a new
Tamil militia accused of killing 38 Moslem policemen in the eastern
Ampara district.
   Fighting that broke out early Thursday tapered off Saturday in a
power struggle that followed last month's departure of 4,000 Indian
peacekeeping soldiers.
   According to reports from the area, the Tamil militia initially
attacked Moslem policemen and civilians. Then the predominantly
Sinhalese Sri Lankan army, backed by helicopter gunships, swept in
to rout the Tamil militiamen.
   About 70 people may have been killed in the two days of
fighting, according to reports from government officials and local
residents.
   On Saturday, hundreds of Sri Lankan soldiers moved into six
camps used by the militia, which calls itself the Tamil National
Army, free-lance photojournalist Jake Gavin said from Ampara.
   Gavin quoted an army brigadier as saying the situation in Ampara
was under control but at least 50 people had died.
   ``The so-called Tamil National Army has been neutralized in
Ampara. We have taken over their camps, and we figure at least 500
members of this illegal army were in existence in Ampara and are
now on the run,'' the brigadier was quoted as saying. He refused to
give his name.
   The government said earlier the Tamil militiamen attacked four
police stations within a 15-mile radius of Ampara early Friday. It
said at least 18 policemen and soldiers and 25 militiamen died in
the fighting in nearby Kalmunai, Sammanturai, Akkaripattu and
Chavalakady.
   Gavin said residents reported at least 38 unarmed policemen were
massacred in Karativu alone early Friday. He said Ampara residents,
adding up various reports, believed at least 72 people died in
fighting throughout the district.
   The Ampara district in on Sri Lanka's east coast, where the
population is about equally divided among Tamils, Sinhalese and
Moslems. Ampara is part of the area where Tamil separatists tried
to set up an independent homeland by massacring or driving out
Sinhalese in the mid-1980s.
   India has agreed to withdraw all its 40,000 troops from Sri
Lanka by Dec. 31. They were deployed in 1987 to help enforce a plan
to grant Tamils limited autonomy in the north and east. The mainly
Hindu Tamils say the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority
descriminates against them.
   India was drawn into the internal affairs of its small island
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own politically powerful
Tamil minority.
   India was to supervise a surrender of arms by Tamil guerrillas.
But the largest Tamil militia, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, reneged on the deal. Indian soon found itself bogged down in
a jungle war with the Tamil Tigers, the same group that once found
sanctuary on Indian soil for its battle against Sri Lanka's
Sinhalese majority.
   Sinhhalese make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people
and Tamils comprise 18 percent. Seven percent of the population is
Moslem, a group largely immune from the ethnic violence until the
last two years when they started coming under attack from Tamil
militants.
   At least 11,000 people, including 1,100 Indian soldiers, have
died in the Tamil separatist war since 1983.
</TEXT>
