<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Bus     11-18 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Bus,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Killed, 48 Injured In Tourist Bus Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tourist bus on a foggy Golan Heights highway
apparently swerved to avoid a car and overturned into a ravine
Saturday, killing a West German woman and injuring 50 others
aboard, police said.
   Druse Moslem villagers, Jewish settlers, military doctors and
emergency medical service workers from the nearby town of Kiryat
Shmona helped in the rescue operations.
   Those hurt included 48 tourists from West Germany, an Israeli
guide for the group and the driver, an Arab from east Jerusalem,
police said.
   No injuries were reported among the passengers of the car, which
left the scene of the accident.
   Police said the accident occurred on the Masada-Banias road in
the Israeli-annexed Golan Heights and that the bus apparently
swerved to avoid a collision with a car that came in the opposite
direction and grazed the bus.
   Witnesses said the bus overturned and rolled for about 50 yards
down the slope of a steep ravine before being stopped by old oak
trees and boulders. The vehicle remained on its roof, they said.
   Boaz Norkin, head of emergency medical service in Kiryat Shmona,
said the injuries included bruises, cuts and broken limbs. He said
the injured were taken to a hospital in the Galilee town of Safed,
where they were reported to be out of danger.
   The name of the dead woman was not released. Israel radio said
families of the victims, elderly West Germans, were informed of the
accident through their country's embassy in Israel.
</TEXT>
