<DOCNO> AP891118-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     11-18 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Kills 3 British Soldiers; IRA Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A roadside blast killed three
British soldiers on patrol in Northern Ireland on Saturday, hours
after a car bomb at an English garrison town injured an army
sergeant and his wife.
   The sergeant lost both legs in the explosion, Essex county
police said.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility, but police and the
Home Office suspected the Irish Republican Army, which has targeted
army installations in England and continental Europe as well as
Northern Ireland in its bloody campaign to drive the British out of
the province.
   The British army patrol was in two armored Land-Rovers in the
foothills of the Mourne Mountains, about six miles from the Irish
Republic, when an explosive device was detonated, apparently from
beside the road, the Royal Ulster Constabulary said.
   The blast hurled the first vehicle off the road. All the
casualties were in that vehicle, police said. The men in the second
vehicle ecaped injury.
   Helicopters flew into the area to help the injured soldiers, but
three died before they could be treated, police said. A fourth was
seriously injured and hospitalized in Belfast.
   At the British army headquarters for eastern England in
Colchester, 50 miles northeast of London, a car bomb exploded as
off-duty staff Sgt. Andrew Mudd and his wife were setting out from
the parking area at the married quarters, police said. The two were
dragged from the burning wreckage of their car by a lieutenant who
was driving past, witnesses said.
   One neighbor said the car was ``a mass of flames.''
   Ronald Tuckwell, who lives nearby, said he saw the car on fire
from his bedroom window. ``People had pulled the occupants out when
there was a sudden burst of flames and the whole car was
engulfed,'' he said.
   His neighbor John Clouting said, ``The front of the car was
blown apart. I could not see very much because of the smoke.
   ``I knew people had been injured because someone was carrying a
white quilt to put over them. I could hear screams. It sounded like
a child, but it could have been a woman.''
   Army spokesman Gordon Williams said, ``The soldier involved was
off duty. I suppose he would be going shopping with his wife, doing
the normal Saturday things.''
   The couple were taken to Colchester General Hospital where
General Manager Mark Shackell said Mudd had lost both legs and was
in serious condition in the intensive therapy unit after 4{ hours
of surgery. He said Mudd's wife, whose name was not released,
suffered ``relatively minor'' injuries.
   David Waddington, the Home Office secretary, blamed the outlawed
IRA, which is trying to end British rule in the predominantly
Protestant province and unite it with the Roman Catholic Irish
Republic.
   ``They will never be allowed to achieve by the bomb and the
bullet what they cannot achieve through the ballot box,''
Waddington said.
   Authorities sealed off part of Colchester, the third-largest
garrison town in Britain. Houses near the scene of the blast were
evacuated as bomb squad officers conducted an investigation.
   About 4,500 troops are based at Colchester, which is army
headquarters for the 11-county eastern district.
   The Ministry of Defense stepped up security at military
establishments across Britain after the Sept. 22 IRA bombing at the
Royal Marines Music School in Deal, southeast England, that killed
11 men.
   The IRA has also claimed responsibility for a series of attacks
on British servicemen and their families in West Germany. A
soldier's wife was killed this summer and a 6-month-old girl died
last month with her father, a Royal Air Force corporal, in an IRA
attack.
   Since the province's sectarian fighting began in 1969, 266
police, 601 army personnel, and 1,902 civilians have been killed.
</TEXT>
