<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-Shopping     11-18 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Shopping,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Super Day for Woolworth in West Berlin, Slow Sales at Upscale Shops</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BER1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A super Saturday for Woolworth's was a lost
weekend for its snootier neighbors on West Berlin's elegant
Kurfuerstendamm shopping strip.
   For the second straight weekend, East Berliners jammed the
sidewalks around the ``Ku'damm,'' as the street is known, until
police blocked off streets to handle the overflow.
   ``We're the ones who feel walled in,'' complained a manager at
Leiser, a store with little choice but to push cheap sneakers
instead of expensive footware on the street named after ranking
German princes of the Holy Roman Empire.
   East Germans, with their $54 of ``welcome money'' from the West
German government, couldn't afford the more expensive fare.
   Trash bins were full to the brim with beer bottles, pop cans and
banana skins, a reminder that East Berliners call West Germany a
``banana republic'' and mean it as a compliment because the
tropical fruit is so rare back home.
   There were no free bottles of champagne this weekend, but there
was the same feeling of good cheer and even a little nostalgia for
the giddy days just after the opening of the Berlin Wall on Nov. 9.
   Sidewalk merchants hawked T-shirts and buttons bearing the magic
Nov. 9 date and the boast: ``Ich war dabei!'' _ I was there.
   Katrin Kupfer, 16, and three companions from Dresden said they
had each spent all of their $54 of ``welcome money'' from the West
German government, buying clothes and a Walkman and saving money by
sleeping all night in a shopping center.
   ``When I got here I thought I was hallucinating, there were so
many lights,'' she said. ``At 3 a.m., people are still coming and
going here. At home, forget it.''
   Gerd Friedrich had his family up at 6 a.m. to drive in from
Leipzig, and they went to the upscale Ka De We department store to
buy chewing gum and candy bars for the return trip. ``It's a little
more costly here, but back home it doesn't taste as good,'' said
his son Lars, 10.
   At Woolworths, crowds were so heavy that employees controlled
the doors and made some people wait. ``A very big day,'' especially
for chocolates, cosmetics and toys, manager Martin Woestmann told a
reporter.
   ``Another day, I'd have more time. Not now,'' he said
apologetically, and darted down an aisle.
   The manager at the Leiser shoe store wouldn't give her name _
she was just a branch manager, she explained _ but she wasn't
withholding her misgivings about the new West Berlin.
   ``The only thing we can sell are these tall sneakers,'' she
said, pointing to a rack on the sidewalk, not the place where her
store usually displays merchandise.
   This Saturday, the market was for $21 sneakers and $5.40 socks,
not for $215 wingtips or sleek pumps.
   ``It is very difficult for our customers,'' said the manager,
whose fur-trimmed black leather coat set her apart from the
shoppers in well-worn cloth coats.
   Beneath the World War II-damaged tower of Berlin's famous
Memorial Church, the free market of ideas was bustling.
   ``We need a coordinated traffic plan,'' said a speaker at
talkfest set up by the Social Democratic Party and inflicted on the
masses by huge loudspeakers.
   ``Germany needs Jesus Christ,'' said a Seventh-day Adventist
preacher with a lower-powered microphone. A little ways away, a
dour woman in a blue raincoat wore a placard extolling the joys of
free love, while Hare Krishnas tinkled their cymbals nearby.
   ``Test the West!'' said one big banner _ not the way of life,
but a brand of cigarette. Employees offered to swap East German
smokes for their brand and found plenty of takers.
   One West Berliner had parked a truckload of beer along the
sidewalk and pitched one-pint cans at $1.10 each.
   ``Come closer!,'' he yelled. ``We'll rip you off just like the
next stand.'' That got a good laugh from the East Berliners.
   Kurfursten, or electors, were German princes entitled to take
part in choosing the sovereign head of the Holy Roman Empire, which
existed from 962 to 1806. Damm is German for roadway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891118-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Mood 1stLd-Writethru   11-18 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Mood, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0575,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Majority of Salvadorans Say They're Fed Up With Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 9th, `About 2,000...' to UPDATE with today's
developments. Pickup 10th, `Casualty figures...' Note contents of 18th
graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The silent majority of
Salvadorans, who never have taken sides with the rightist
government or the leftist guerrillas, are damning them both for
turning their neighborhoods into battlegrounds.
   Fear and desperation have the run of bloody streets barely
traveled by city dwellers, who live day in and day out through
combat and curfew. The massacre and mutilation of six priests, all
prominent educators, added to the terror.
   Speaking with a reporter Friday in the capital's battle-ravaged
Soyapango district, the father of a family of five criticized both
the government for sending warplanes to rocket and strafe his block
and the dug-in guerrillas who converted the neighborhood into a
military objective.
   Asked his name, he provided it, and the reporter wrote it down
in his notebook.
   ``Wait a minute,'' the man said, and calmly took pen and pad
from the journalist's hand and blacked out his name.
   ``They'll come and get me, and I'll end up like her,'' he
explained, nodding toward a girl about 13 years old, lying dead six
feet away.
   The girl had ventured out in search of food during a lull in
combat and was felled, apparently by a stray bullet.
   It has been battle after battle since some 2,000 Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front rebels descended on San Salvador and its
1 million people on the evening of Nov. 11 and turned it into a war
zone.
   About 2,000 more attacked dozens of targets in other parts of
the country. The fighting here and elsewhere continued throughout
the week, and relief workers have been unable to evacuate the
wounded or remove bodies.
   The fighting slackened Saturday, allowing thousands of exhausted
residents to evacuate with their children and whatever possessions
they could carry.
   Casualty figures are sketchy. Hospital and military sources
estimate that more than 800 people have been killed and 2,000
wounded.
   In the combat zones, decomposing bodies lie here and there,
shiny bloated semblances of human bodies, a nauseating odor filling
the air.
   ``We're not with one side or the other, thank God,'' Marta
Rodriguez said as she and her family closed their house in the
devastated Soyapango section of Conacaste, scene of some of the
fiercest alley-to-alley and house-to-house fighting, and fled the
area.
   Each of her family of five had eaten one tortilla with a few
sips of coffee Thursday, when they ran out of everything except a
gallon of water.
   The facade of their humble cinderblock home was cratered with
bullet and shrapnel holes, the yellow metal door sporting seven
bullet holes, and part of the roof blown off.
   ``The two sides must join in a heartfelt dialogue. They must
abandon the idea of dialogue as something strategic,'' said Carlos,
her husband.
   It is a call echoed by many here and in the rest of Central
America to end the 10-year-old civil war that has killed more than
70,000 people, most of them civilians.
   In one of the war's most barbaric acts, a death squad entered
the Jesuit-run Central American University on the city's southern
edge before dawn Thursday and broke into the residence where the
rector, the vice-rector and four other educators were sleeping.
   The victims, all members of the Society of Jesus, were awakened,
slaughtered and their brains removed.
   It was a pointed message to other intellectuals who, like the
progressive priests, sought to elaborate on the need for change in
a society that has benefited few while condemning the great
majority to ignorance, misery and early death.
   University officials said witnesses saw 30 men in army uniforms
enter the priests' residence just before the shooting. However, the
U.S.-backed right-wing government denounced the killings and said
it would investigate.
   A state of siege suspending most individual liberties and
guarantees has been in effect a week. In many regards, the measure
does not affect the lives of the poor, whose right to life and
liberty _ much less the pursuit of happiness _ has never been paid
more than lip service.
   The measure imposes censorship and voids freedom of expression.
   It also has drastically altered radio programming _ and the
radio is in most cases the poor Salvadoran's only link to the world
beyond his adobe house, cornfield or slum.
   The government has obliged all stations to plug into an official
network, on which enthusiastic announcers describe a capital
rapidly returning to normal, of stoic and smiling workers and
homemakers resuming their routines.
   ``The government says it's got everything under control, that
everything is fine,'' said another man in Soyapango, who like
hundreds of desperate residents was out looking for some place to
buy some beans or bread.
   ``But we're being badly informed, as you can see for yourself,''
he said, pointing two blocks down the road where guerrillas with
assault rifles and a grenade-launcher manned a barricade that
isolated the district.
</TEXT>
