<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-Doctors     11-18 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Doctors,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exodus of Doctors, Nurses Hits Medical Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARL MARX STADT, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only gynecologist
serving an area of 110,000 people has left without warning, just
one indication of how the exodus of East Germans to the West has
caused a health care crisis.
   ``This is dramatic, of course,'' Dr. Hanns Wohlfarth, the acting
chief district physician, said of the gynecologist's departure to
the West from Karl Marx Stadt.
   By the end of September, before the government suddenly dropped
travel barriers, 100 doctors and 500 other medical staff had left
the Karl Marx Stadt district, Wohlfarth said Friday in an interview
with The Associated Press.
   The district's combined areas have a population of 2 million
people.
   He added that the subsequent opening of routes to the West made
it ``certain that the number has doubled by now, and may have
increased even further.''
   Other authorities estimate that 10 percent of East Germany's
doctors have emigrated, either legally or illegally. Wohlfarth said
Karl Marx Stadt, a city in southern East Germany, is among the
hardest hit.
   ``In some hospitals there is an emergency situation,'' he said,
citing the example of one nurse doing the work of four.
   But he said vital functions including intensive care and urgent
surgery have not been affected so far.
   This is partly because hundreds of people have been switched
from other jobs to replace ambulance drivers, technicians and
administrative staff who left, he said. About 300 army conscripts
are expected to join the support staff soon.
   Wohlfarth, a practicing dermatologist and a member of the
Communist Party, said he was ``personally shocked'' by the
departure of the doctors.
   He said it would be a ``genuine help'' if young doctors from
West Germany would temporarily replace those who had left.
   ``But it is much more important that the many East German
doctors and dentists who left come back. Think of their medical
ethics and, above all, think of the patients they left behind,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
