<HEAD>Eastern European Events at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd pvs, `In Leipzig...' to UPDATE with rallies
in three other East German cities; picks up 4th pvs, `BULGARIA _ In ...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at major developments in Eastern Europe on
Saturday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EAST GERMANY _ Parliament swears in a new reform-minded Cabinet
and sets up a committee to study possible constitutional changes,
including stripping the Communist Party of its monopoly on power.
   In Leipzig, about 10,000 people rally to demand free elections.
But most East Germans use their day off to once again flock over
the border for a taste of capitalism in West Berlin.
   Pro-democracy supporters also taje to the streets in Plauen,
Eberswalde-Finow and Suhl.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BULGARIA _ In the biggest independent protest rally in Communist
Bulgaria's history, about 50,000 people call for political reform
and the punishment of former Communist Party chief Todor Zhivkov,
who was ousted one week ago.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CZECHOSLOVAKIA _ Protesters light candles and place flowers on
bloodstained sidewalks in Prague, where police a day earlier
clubbed hundreds of peaceful pro-democracy demonstrators. Students
and actors call for a general strike Nov. 27 to protest police
brutality.
   At the same time, Czechoslovak officials in Sweden announce that
Czechoslovakia's leading dissident, playwright Vaclav Havel, is
being allowed to travel to Stockholm this week to accept the Olof
Palme human rights award.
