<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Latvia     11-18 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latvians Celebrate Independence Day at Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Lativians rallied Saturday in
the republic's capital of Riga to celebrate the 71st anniversary of
its declaration of independence.
   Anda Anspoka, a spokesman for the Latvian People's Front said,
said between 400,000 and 500,000 people gathered along the banks of
the Daugava River to commemorate the Soviet republic's former
independence, declared on Nov. 18, 1918 and lasting until Soviet
occupation in 1940.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, estimated the crowd at
tens of thousands, including Latvian President Anatoly Gorbunov and
the republic's Communist Party leader, Janis Vagris.
   Gorbunov told local television reporters that he was there
because he believed that Latvia should become independent once
again, Anspoka said. The Tass dispatch did not mention that.
   On Nov. 11, the Latvian Supreme Soviet, or parliament, declared
Nov. 18 an official holiday and approved the rally.
   Activists at the rally waved placards demanding independence and
the demiliarization of Latvia, Anspoka said in a telephone
interview.
   Nearly every fifth person carried the national red and white
flags at the rally, the spokesman said. ``The place resembled a sea
of flags, a very impressing and spectacular sight.''
   He said the rally was well organized, with railway schedules
changed to accommodate Latvians who wanted to attend. According to
Anspoka, police presence was negligible and there were no reports
of violence or disorder.
</TEXT>
