<FIRST>u a AM-TrailerFire     11-18 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trailer Fire,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Children, One Adult Die In Trailer Blaze</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cystal is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAXTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early morning fire torched a crowded
mobile home Saturday, killing a woman and eight children, while the
mother of three of the victims watched helplessly screaming ``My
babies! My babies!'', officials and witnesses said.
   ``We're thinking it may have come from one of the kerosene-type
portable heaters,'' said Jimmy Maynor, chief of detectives for the
Robeson County Sheriff's Department. ``We're not positive on that.''
   Temperatures had dropped to about 32 degrees when the blaze
broke out about 4 a.m. in a trailer owned by Lois Ann Hunt, 32,
officials said.
   Maynor identified the victims as Mrs. Hunt, 32; her children,
Alisha Ann Hunt, 12; Melissa Sue Hunt, 11; Bobby Ray Hunt, 3; Nikki
Marie Hunt, 3; and Larry James Dial, 5; and three other children,
Cystal Lynn Locklear, 5; Glenford Locklear, 4; and Daniel Presley
Locklear Jr., 2.
   The Locklears were the children of JoAnn Locklear, 25, of
Maxton, who escaped with a burn to her left arm. Her boyfriend,
Richard Eugene Tyndall, 22, of Laurinburg, also escaped. He
received a cut to his hand after trying to get back into the house
through a window to rescue the others, Maynor said.
   Tyndall also had to restrain Ms. Locklear from running back into
the burning trailer, said a neighbor, Angie Locklear.
   ``She was hollering, `My babies! My babies!','' said Angie
Locklear. ``She wanted to go back in and get them.''
   By the time firefighters arrived, the trailer was engulfed in
flames, officials said.
   Angie Locklear said she heard an explosion and first thought it
was a gunshot, but ``when I looked out, all I could see were
flames.'' It was not immediately clear whether the two Locklear
women are related; the name is common in the region.
   Two of the bodies were found in one bedroom, six in another
bedroom and the woman was in a bedroom by herself.
   ``I have been told they were calling for help, so they probably
perished from flames,'' Maynor said.
   An arson team was at the scene sifting through the remains of
the trailer, which was destroyed. Behind the trailer, hogs and
goats were kept in sheds and two lines of clothes were hanging out
to dry.
   Neighbors said Mrs. Hunt had moved her mobile home to the wooded
lot located near U.S. 71 about a year ago and had just started work
at a fast food restaurant three weeks ago.
</TEXT>
