<FIRST>r a AM-SuspectSlain     11-18 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suspect Slain,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Accused in Drug Agent's Death Killed in Apparent Mob Hit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Costabile is cq according to DEA.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mob bosses probably ordered the killing of a
low-level associate accused of murdering a federal drug agent this
year, authorities said Saturday.
   ``Mob justice isn't always swift, but it's always deadly, and
this may be an example of deadly mob justice,'' James Fox, head of
the New York FBI office, said at a news conference.
   Costabile ``Gus'' Farace, 29, was shot Friday night as he sat in
a car, the same manner in which he was accused of killing Everett
Hatcher, a Drug Enforcement Administration agent who was posing as
a drug buyer.
   Hatcher's death Feb. 28 sparked a manhunt that involved up to
100 federal agents working seven days a week, and it prbably made
the Mafia bosses angry, said U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney.
   ``It's reasonable to assume all of that pressure could have
resulted in last night's shooting,'' Maloney said. ``The intensity
of the investigation never faltered. It was a full court press as
recently as yesterday.''
   Farace also was to be featured Sunday as the country's ``No. 1
fugitive'' on the Fox network television show ``America's Most
Wanted.''
   Maloney described Farace, who was paroled in 1988 after serving
eight years for a kidnap-murder, as a ``young punk'' associated
with the Bonanno and Colombo crime groups.
   ``I think it's reasonable to assume organized crime figures were
aware of the intensity of the investigation,'' Maloney said. ``I
assume that people higher up were as interested in finding him as
we were.''
   Robert Stutman, head of the DEA's New York office said: ``A
rational and prudent person would obviously believe that this is
probably a mob hit. The investigation is continuing; I can't say
that for sure.''
   Stutman said Farace, who grew a beard and dyed his hair red
while hiding out, apparently never left New York City. He said
agents at times had come within two hours of Farace but he always
disappeared with the help of mob associates.
   Authorities hoped that by capturing Farace they could make him
the first defendant to face the death penalty under a new federal
drug law, Stutman said.
   ``It would have been nice to see him sitting there and
squirming, knowing he'd never see the streets again,'' Stutman said.
   Hatcher, 46, was shot to death in February on Staten Island
after he went to meet Farace to set up a cocaine deal in an
undercover operation, authorities said.
   On Friday, Farace was sitting in the front passenger seat of a
car double parked on a Brooklyn street when a van pulled alongside
about 11 p.m. Seven to nine shots were fired into the car, Maloney
said.
   Farace was found dead. The driver, Joseph Sclafani, who had been
hit in the chest three times, got out of the car and fired a few
shots from his .38-caliber handgun at the fleeing van, Maloney said.
   Sclafani, 24, was listed in critical condition at Coney Island
Hospital.
</TEXT>
