<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     11-18 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Imposes Travel Restrictions, Security Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania has imposed security checks and
travel restrictions on travelers seeking to enter or leave the
country.
   Police near the border with Hungary were removing Romanian
citizens from trains leaving the country and turning many back,
according to other passengers.
   The restrictions, coming in advance of a Communist Party
congress, began Friday. Travelers aboard one train said at least 70
people were ordered off and some were subjected to body searches.
   Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu has rejected the political
and economic reforms sweeping Hungary and Romania's other Warsaw
Pact allies.
   Tanjug, the Yugoslav news agency, reported vehicles with foreign
license plates were being checked by Romanian border police and
said ``this is a sign of the difficult situation surrounding the
14th congress'' of the Romanian Communist Party that opens Monday.
   In a report from the Romanian capital of Bucharest, Tanjug said
security measures were increased throughout Romania and identity
checks were being carried out at airports and railroad and bus
stations.
   Tamas Oltvanyi, reporting for Hungarian state television from
Bucharest, said all roads leading to the Romanian capital were
controlled by police and ``people are being turned back at the
border.''
   Hungarian Lt. Col. Laszlo Fenyoe said that on Saturday 575 of
1,308 people planning to travel from Hungary to Romania were
refused entry by border police regardless of their nationality or
destination. He said those travelers were not given any reason but
on Friday police told some of the people turned back that ``the
hotels are full.''
   ``Those being turned away include not only Hungarians but also
Czechoslovaks, Turks, Dutch, West Germans, Poles, you name it,''
Fenyoe told The Associated Press.
   The Hungarian news agency MTI said at the Hungarian Nagylak
border crossing trucks were delayed for 10-12 hours Saturday before
being allowed to proceed and no reason was given for the blockage.
   A duty officer at the Romanian Embasy in Budapest said he had
not been notified ``about any such problems.''
   Hungarian-Romanian relations were difficult even before
Ceausescu's government maintaianed its hard-line stand against
reforms. Hungary has accused Romania of discriminating against the
1.7 million ethnic Hungarians living in Romania who claim they are
denied essential rights as a minority.
</TEXT>
