<FIRST>r a AM-GroundedShip     11-18 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grounded Ship,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Plans Cleanup Next Week After Ship Runs Aground in Bering
Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanup of oil from a Greek cargo ship
that ran aground in the Bering Sea will begin sometime next week,
with the start-up time depending largely on the weather, the Coast
Guard said.
   Representatives of the Coast Guard and the ship's owner went to
the scene Friday to assess options for oil cleanup and the ship's
salvage.
   The 485-foot Milos Reefer ran aground in 57 mph winds and
22-foot seas late Tuesday off St. Matthew Island, about 250 miles
off the west coast of Alaska in the Bering Sea National Wildlife
Refuge.
   The ship had no cargo, but tanks carrying 258,000 gallons of
fuel oil and 71,320 gallons of diesel oil were damaged.
   Officials haven't determined how much oil spilled, but a survey
Thursday indicated about 2,000 gallons of heavy oil were in the
water near the ship. A lighter slick of undertermined size was seen
about six miles to the northeast.
   Observers in an aircraft Friday saw heavy patches of oil between
the ship and a beach, Coast Guard spokesman Ed Moreth said.
   No damage to birds or wildlife has been documented, the Coast
Guard said. Thirty walruses were seen on a nearby island.
   St. Matthew Island has no human inhabitants and provides summer
nesting areas for birds. State environmental officials are
concerned rats from the ship will swim to the island and damage
nesting sites.
   Burning the Milos Reefer to destroy fuel and rats is a
possibility if other salvage options are unworkable, said Bill
Lamoreaux of the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation.
   The ship's owner, Transcontinental Maritime Trading of Piraeus,
Greece, has accepted financial responsiblity for the accident and
the spill. The 27 crew members were transferred Wednesday onto a
Polish ship that took them to Dutch Harbor.
   Two Coast Guard C-130 transport planes from Sacramento, Calif.,
arrived Thursday night in Kodiak with pumps, containment booms and
other spill equipment.
   The cutter Midgett left Kodiak Friday to serve as the operations
platform for cleanup work, and is expected to reach the spill scene
early in the week. The buoy tender Firebush, based in Kodiak, will
ferry cleanup equipment to St. Matthew Island.
</TEXT>
