<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Czechoslovak     11-18 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Czechoslovak,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Reports `Open' Talks on Naming Czechoslovak Bishops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican said Saturday it completed
``open and cordial'' talks this week with Czechoslovakia on the
appointment of new bishops in the Communist country.
   The talks, from Tuesday through Thursday in Rome, focused on
``issues concerning the life of the Catholic Church in
Czechoslovakia and, in particular, several bishops' nominations,''
the statement said.
   ``The results of the talks will be presented to respective
higher authorities for further consideration,'' it said.
   Church-state relations generally have been cold in the Communist
country, and seven of Czechoslovakia's 13 dioceses still have no
bishops.
   But there have been signs of a thaw.
   In June, the Roman Catholic Church succeeded in placing three
new bishops in Czechoslovakia, the first new bishops there in 15
years.
   An estimated 10,000 Czechoslovak pilgrims were allowed to attend
the Nov. 12 beatification in Rome of Agnes of Bohemia, a
Prague-born nun, and the ceremony was broadcast live on
Czechoslovak state television.
