<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-18 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow In Lower Great Lakes, Cold Grips Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snowstorms blanketed the lower Great Lakes on Saturday, dropping
up to a foot of snow in northeast Ohio and causing a rash of
accidents, and unseasonably cold weather chilled the nation's upper
midsection.
   Snow showers reached from much of New York state to northwest
Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan. Up to 8 inches of snow was
forecast for northwest New York state. Scattered snow fell on
northern Maine, as well as southeastern North Dakota and eastern
South Dakota.
   In northeast Ohio, travel near Lake Erie was hazardous if not
impossible in some areas, the National Weather Service said.
Columbus got only a dusting of snow overnight, but it formed ice on
bridges, closing Interstate 70 through downtown.
   There was a rash of accidents, including a 15-car pileup on
I-70. Near the eastern Ohio town of St. Clairsville, a van carrying
members of the Muskingum College women's basketball team was hit by
a tractor-trailer on the icy interstate, killing two women and
injuring five.
   Rain fell in south-central Texas, along the upper Texas coast
and in northwest Florida and northwest Oregon.
   During the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST, 2 inches of snow fell
at Traverse City, Mich., and 1 inch fell at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.
   Winds gusted to 60 mph at Vedauwoo between Cheyenne and Laramie,
Wyo. Wind advisories were posted for the mountains of Southern
California, as well as areas below major passes and canyons. A
high-wind watch was posted through Sunday for the mountains of
Wyoming.
   Unseasonably low temperatures settled across the Upper
Mississippi Valley and the Upper Great Lakes.
   Low-temperature records for the date were set in Alpena, Mich.,
where it was 9 degrees; Burlington, Iowa, 10 degrees; Duluth,
Minn., 0; Lamoni, Iowa, 11; Mason City, Iowa; 0; Rochester, Minn.,
minus 4; Sioux City, Iowa, 4; Spencer, Iowa, 4; and Waterloo, Iowa,
5.
   The low temperature for the Lower 48 states Saturday was minus
10 at Warroad, Minn.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees at Grand Rapids, Minn., to 80 degrees at Naples, Fla.
</TEXT>
