<FIRST>r a AM-CityOpera     11-18 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Opera,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Opera Musicians Union Approves Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City Opera orchestra members, whose
eight-week strike forced the cancellation of the company's fall
season, formally approved a five-year contract Saturday.
   Members of Local 802 of the Associated Musicians of Greater New
York voted 47-16 to approve the contract, said union spokeswoman
Judy West.
   ``The major issues were the maintenance of guaranteed weeks of
work and the need for the beginning of an approach to parity with
peer opera orchestras,'' the union said in a statement. ``In this
agreement, both issues have been addressed.''
   Martin Oppenheimer, vice chairman of the City Opera, said plans
were under way for the company's spring musical.
   ``We're delighted the fight's over and the playing can begin,''
he said.
   The agreement calls for annual wage increases of about $50 a
week, ending in the fifth year with wages at $1,000 a week. Weekly
wages under the expired contract were $755.
   The strike began Sept. 13, on what would have been opening night
for the City Opera's fall season of 70 performances. The tentative
agreement was announced Nov. 8.
</TEXT>
