<FIRST>r a AM-ColombianExtraditions 1stLd-Writethru a0642 11-18 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombian Extraditions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Suspects Wanted in Miami, North Carolina Extradited</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to ADD number extradited.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two drug suspects wanted on federal charges were
extradited from Colombia to the United States on Saturday as part
of the South American country's continuing crackdown on its cocaine
cartels, authorities said.
   The U.S. Marshals Service took the pair into custody in Bogota
late Friday and flew them to Miami early Saturday.
   Manuel Palma, 49, a Colombian native, was named in a two-count
indictment issued in Miami in 1987 charging him with drug
trafficking and money laundering, a news release from the Marshals
Service in Washington said.
   He was expected to make an initial court appearance Monday
before a federal magistrate.
   Robert James Sokol, 29, was flown on to Greensboro, N.C., to
face a narcotics conspiracy indictment issued in 1984, the release
said. He was being held without bond in the Guilford County Jail, a
jail spokesman said.
   Fred Gregory of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in
Greensboro said Sokol will probably have a court hearing Monday or
Tuesday. Sokol was living in Greensboro when the indictment was
issued but fled the country, Gregory said in a telephone interview
from his home.
   ``I'm glad to see us get it over with,'' Gregory said. ``There's
a lot more that need to come back. Thank goodness the process is
continuing to work. It was logjammed for so long.''
   The indictments are part of a campaign started in August by the
Colombian government to attack the country's cocaine rings. The
cartels have responded with a campaign of violence that has
included widespread bombings and attacks on government officials
and journalists.
   The latest extraditions bring to eight the number of people
Colombia has turned over to the United States. None of those
extradited have been among the dozen major traffickers sought by
U.S. authorities.
</TEXT>
