<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru   11-18 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0609,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Approves Cabinet, Warns of Black-Market Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protest in West Berlin; picks
up 10th pvs, `In East...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BER100</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's Parliament approved a
reform-minded Cabinet on Saturday as the Communist government
begged millions heading West to avoid black-market currency dealing
that further damages their economy.
   Lawmakers created a committee to study possible constitutional
changes, including stripping the Communists of their 40-year
monopoly on power. And new Communist leaders threatened to
investigate their hard-line predecessors for corruption and abuse
of power.
   About 10,000 peopled joined a pro-democracy protest in Leipzig,
where organizers said many skipped the rally to go shopping in West
Germany. Protesters demanded free elections and a genuine political
opposition force.
   Pro-democracy supporters also took to the streets in three other
cities, Plauen, Eberswalde-Finow and Suhl, the official East German
news agency ADN said late Saturday. It estimated 22,000 people took
part.
   Hundreds of thousands of other East Germans jammed trains and
highways into West Germany, creating a 19-mile backup at one
Bavarian border crossing and overwhelming public transport headed
West.
   For more than 1.6 million other East Germans, Saturday was a day
of shopping and sightseeing in West Berlin and West Germany, fueled
for many by $54 in ``welcome money'' per person from the government
in Bonn. West Berlin's shopping avenues became pedestrian malls.
   Some trains were ``recklessly stormed'' by impatient travelers
who filled the cars two or three times over capacity, the official
ADN news agency reported.
   People in West Germany greeted tourists with free lodging,
well-stocked store shelves and just plain curiosity.
   Late Saturday, West Berlin leftists scuffled with police during
a demonstration staged over the killing Friday of a woman during a
protest in the West German city of Goettingen. The woman was struck
by a car while fleeing police who had moved in to disperse the
protesters in Goettingen.
   Throngs of visiting East Germans looked on as West Berlin police
made arrests.
   In East Berlin, Premier Hans Modrow's 28-member Cabinet was
immediately sworn in after receiving approval from the 500-member
People's Chamber. The Cabinet was named as the government came
under increasing pressure to institute reforms and loosen the
Communists' grip on power.
   Eleven deputies are non-Communists, but they belong to political
parties long aligned with the ruling force. Reform groups like
Democracy Now and New Forum also are agitating for a role in
government affairs.
   At a news conference attended by several new Cabinet members and
other government officials, Foreign Minister Oskar Fischer said:
``I see concern abroad about a possible instability occuring in
this country.'' Fischer added that the other European countries are
not interested in seeing any such political ``shock'' on the
continent.
   The foreign minister also expressed interest in better ties to
the European Economic Community.
   Also at the news conference, Finance Minister Uta Nickel
appealed for patriotism in refraining from currency speculation.
   Illegal trading of non-convertible East German marks has become
rampant over the past week as East Germans visiting the West trade
money for 20 times less than the official rate set by East Berlin.
   ``Immediate measures are needed to protect the currency,'' Mrs.
Nickel said. ``We appeal from our hearts for an end to money
speculations.'' She did not specify what actions were needed.
   East German border guards were quoted by ADN as saying they
confiscated as much as 9,000 marks _ about $4,900 at the official
rate _ from tourists headed West. East Germans are forbidden from
leaving with more than 300 marks.
   Modrow has called for economic reforms but ruled out the idea of
a free-market economy.
   The East German Parliament formed a committee to investigate
cases of corruption, personal enrichment and abuse of power.
   Communist Party chief Egon Krenz was quoted as strongly
indicating the panel would investigate the activities of his
predecessor and mentor, Erich Honecker, as well as other top
leaders of the hard-line regime ousted over the past month. Krenz
replaced Honecker on Oct. 18.
   ``The responsibility of former General Secretary Honecker and
former Politburo members Guenter Mittag and Joachim Hermann are
names that have been concretely identified. We are not covering
up,'' Krenz was quoted as saying by the Hamburg-based Bild am
Sonntag newspaper.
   East German authorities have issued more than 10 million exit
visas, ADN said. That means more than 60 percent of the population
has obtained authorization to visit the West.
   The agency said 10.1 million visas have been issued since Nov.
9, when travel restrictions were lifted on East Germany's 16.5
million people. About 200,000 East Germans have moved to West
Germany and West Berlin this year.
</TEXT>
