<FIRST>u a AM-School-StormFunerals 1stLd-Writethru a06</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School-Storm Funerals, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0631,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funerals Begin For East Coldenham Tornado Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to RECAST, moving up detail from services; UPDATES
with state, local officials meeting, engineers examining wall, three children
getting look at cafeteria. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children sobbed and clutched their parents
Saturday at services for two 8-year-olds killed when a tornado
smashed a wall in their elementary school's cafeteria.
   ``Everybody's heart is heavy,'' Alice Marinelli, great aunt of
Larae Litchhult, said at the girl's private funeral.
   At a funeral home in nearby New Windsor, the Rev. Ted Bechtel
urged relatives and friends of Peter Orsino to ``not grieve as
those who have no hope.''
   Larae and Peter were among seven school children killed Thursday
when the wall blew in at the East Coldenham Elementary School
shortly after noon, showering cinder blocks and glass on lunching
first-, second- and third-graders.
   Services for the other five tornado victims were scheduled for
Monday.
   ``Everybody is very sad. She was a sweet little girl,'' said Ed
Batdorf, a friend of the Litchhult family who was among the 50
mourners attending her private funeral.
   ``Right now she's not suffering,'' Batdorf continued. ``She's in
Jehovah's memory and we look forward to seeing her again.''
   Marinelli said the Litchhult family's loss is being shared by
people throughout the area.
   ``It's certainly a community that has come together in sorrow,''
she said.
   Mourners filled every room of the Coloni Funeral Home for Peter
Orsino's service, and sobbing children held tight to their parents.
   ``A young boy with so much promise is gone from us,'' Bechtel
said. ``The pain doesn't go away tomorrow or next week. But it is
in our sorrow and grief, our anger and our frustration, that we
need to find a way to help us live our todays and our tomorrows
also.
   ``... We will have to build our lives again out of the ashes
that now fill our hearts,'' the minister said.
   While the services took place, officials of the State Emergency
Management Office met with Newburgh officials to assess the damage
to the school. Engineers began examining the wall but have not
determined if structural problems contributed to the collapse, said
Tony Germano, deputy director of the state office.
   ``It's difficult to say,'' he said. ``It's a terrible
situation.''
   At the site itself, a trio of 12-year-olds from a nearby middle
school slipped past police and caught an up-close glimpse of the
destruction. Wide-eyed and out of breath, they told of seeing
spilled milk and food amid the rubble.
   ``Two lunch boxes were still sitting on a table,'' one of them
kept repeating.
   Bob Hayes, vice president of the Coldenham Fire Department in
Newburgh, 60 miles north of New York City, said many of his men
felt they didn't do enough for the young victims.
   ``That first day and even into yesterday things were pretty
tough around here,'' Hayes said. ``We had a lot of people taking it
pretty hard.''
   Thirteen of the 18 students injured remained hospitalized
Saturday. Two were listed in critical condition. The condition of a
third child, who'd been listed as critical Thursday, was upgraded
to fair Saturday.
</TEXT>
