<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nynex     11-18 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nynex,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Implementation Talks Break Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nynex Corp. and union negotiators broke off
talks on implementing a tentative contract agreement, dashing hopes
for an end to a 3-month strike at New York Telephone Co., both
sides said Saturday.
   Officials had hoped to settle local issues by midnight Friday so
that striking workers at Nynex's two subsidiaries, New York
Telephone and New England Telephone Co., could return to work
Monday. The tentative contract agreement was reached last Monday.
   No new sessions were planned for Nynex, New York Telephone and
the 40,000-member Communications Workers of America after talks
broke down late Friday in the New York City suburb of Rye Brook,
officials said.
   In Boston, however, the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers and New England Telephone did come to an agreement on local
issues Friday night.
   The 20,000 IBEW members were to vote Sunday on the pact and,
assuming it passes, could be back on the job Monday, said Adele
Stacy, business agent for IBEW local 2222 in Boston.
   Nynex accused the CWA of reneging on agreements reached earlier
in the week, particularly the question of arbitration for 150
workers who were disciplined during the strike.
   ``They started monkeying around with amnesty for disciplined
employees,'' Nynex spokesman Robert O'Brien said. ``In a nutshell,
we told them to take a hike. There's no way we're going to give on
that one.''
   O'Brien said 82 workers were suspended for offenses like
harassing non-striking employees and destroying management
employees' property, and about 50 were dismissed for assaulting
non-striking employees.
   Bob Master, a CWA spokesman, denied the union had reneged on
agreements. He said the CWA was willing to submit those cases for
arbitration but wanted assurances on who would review the cases,
when they would be submitted and under what circumstances.
   Master said the union also was fighting company demands that
included longer workweeks for certain classes of workers with no
increase in pay and extension of the right to hire temporary
workers.
   The strike, which began Aug. 6, has delayed directory
assistance, repairs and installation for Nynex's 10.5 million
customers in New York, Rhode Island, Massachusetts, New Hampshire,
Vermont, Maine and two cities in Connecticut.
   The dispute is the last of a series of strikes by 200,000
workers in 20 states against Baby Bell regional phone companies.
</TEXT>
