<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     11-18 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Rejects Troop Withdrawals And Exchange Of POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Saturday rejected an Iranian
proposal to exchange prisoners of war if the Iraqis withdrew from
territories taken during the Persian Gulf war.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz told a news conference that Iraq
will not accept any compromise short of redrawing the border to
include the strategic Shatt-al-Arab waterway in Iraqi territory.
   Aziz spoke a day after U.N. envoy Jan Eliasson left Tehran for
New York, ending a 17-day peace mission in the region.
   Eliasson acknowledged that his bid to break the deadlock in
peace talks has failed but said Aziz and his Iranian counterpart,
Ali Akbar Velayati, would meet separately in New York in
mid-December with U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Aziz told the news conference: ``We consider the Shatt as pure
Iraqi territory. When Iran recognizes our sovereignty over the
Shatt, we will be ready to withdraw our forces'' from Iranian
territory.
   The United Nations estimates the Iranian territory Iraq occupies
at 385 square miles, although Tehran claims the area is double that.
   The cease-fire began Aug. 20, 1988, but the talks on a final end
to the 8-year-old war have deadlocked.
   Iran has pushed for implementing the U.N. cease-fire resolution
point by point. Iraq insisted on settling first the issue of
sovereignty over Shatt-al-Arab.
   The resolution makes no reference to Shatt-Al-Arab. In addition
to the cessation of hostilities, it calls for troop withdrawals to
the internationally recognized pre-war border, the exchange of POWs
and settlement of the border dispute through negotiations.
   The channel is Iraq's sole outlet to the gulf. Before the war,
the border ran midstream down Shatt-al-Arab under a 1975 agreement.
   Aziz called the latest Iranian proposal tantamount to
``blackmail.''
   ``The Iranians are using a humanitarian issue as a brgaining
chip,'' he said of the POWs.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross has registered
almost 50,000 prisoners held by Iran, and about 19,000 held by
Iraq. But U.N. estimates place the number of POWs at more than
100,000.
</TEXT>
