<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Election     11-18 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists Battle to Reach Second Round</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative took a berth Saturday in
a two-man presidential runoff but only about 300,000 of the 74.4
million votes counted so far separated two leftists vying for the
second spot, according to official returns.
   With 91.5 of the votes tabulated, Fernando Collor de Mello, of
the center-right National Reconstruction Party, had virtually
guaranteed first place with 24 percent of Wednesday's balloting,
the first free presidential vote since 1960.
   Labor Party candidate Leonel Brizola was running second with
about 10.9 million votes, or 14.6 percent, trailed by Marxist Luis
Inacio Lula da Silva with 10.6 million, or 14.3 percent.
   The top two finishers will compete in the runoff Dec. 17.
   Da Silva, of the radical-left Workers' Party, had led Brizola by
3 percentage points in official tallies until Saturday morning. But
the Superior Electoral Court said Brizola moved past da Silva after
returns came in from the heavily populated states of Rio Grande do
Sul and Rio de Janeiro, Brizola strongolds.
   Da Silva and Brizola have pledged to forget their personal
rivalry that marked the campaign and support the winner of their
battle for second.
</TEXT>
