<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 2241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     11-18 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southerners Vote on Autonomy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in 13 southern provinces
decided Sunday whether to join a regional autonomous government
designed to satisfy Moslem demands for self-rule.
   The military maintained a full alert on southern Mindanao island
but reported no violence in the first hour after polls opened at 7
a.m.
   Polls close at 3 p.m., but results for the entire region is not
expected for several days.
   President Corazon Aquino offered regional autonomy to placate
demands for self-rule by an estimated 4 million Moslems. Moslems
who have waged a nearly 20-year-old insurgency have rejected the
plan as inadequate.
   The armed forces chief of staff, Gen. Renato De Villa, said
Saturday that 50,000 troops and police have deputized by elections
commission to ensure a ``fair and honest'' plebiscite.
   Elections officials reported a moderate early turnout in this
southern port city, 540 miles south of Manila.
   Ustadz Zain Jali, a spokesman for the successionist Moro
National Liberation Front, said there was a very small turnout in
predominantly Moslem villages near the city.
   On Saturday, gunmen killed a Moslem militiaman and four of his
relatives, and bombs exploded in two provinces, police said. A
13-year-old boy was injured in one of the explosions.
   Col. Jesus Almadin, police area commander, said the killings
took place shortly after midnight in a village on the outskirts of
Zamboanga.
   In Lanao del Sur province, a bomb exploded in the provincial
capital building in the city of Marawi, destroying election
materials, police said. There were no reports of casualties, police
said.
   Many Christian voters are expected to reject the autonomy plan,
and Moslems form a majority in only five impoverished and
geographically separated provinces. Only 28 percent of the 3.9
million registered voters are Moslem, election records show.
   Mrs. Aquino forged a cease-fire with the Moslem rebels in 1986.
Peace talks collapsed in May 1987, but the cease-fire generally has
held.
   Before the Moslem rebellion peaked in the mid-1970s, an
estimated 50,000 people were killed and thousands more fled to the
nearby Malaysian state of Sabah.
</TEXT>
