<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 2248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SoldierFuneral     11-18 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soldier Funeral,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airman Buried Two Decades After Crashing in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAKEFIELD, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force flier shot down over Vietnam
more than 20 years ago was buried with full military honors
Saturday in his hometown, and hundreds of residents turned out to
honor him.
   An estimated 500 people, many holding small American flags,
lined Dogwood Street as the funeral procession for Maj. Larry E.
Martin passed by.
   The mile-long procession, led by members of veterans groups on
foot and motorcycle, ended at Highland Cemetary.
   ``You want to see the man come home,'' said Frosty Sheridan, who
like Martin belonged to the 44th Tactical Fighter Squadron.
   Martin, 28, was the co-pilot of an Air Force fighter jet when it
was shot down on July 15, 1968. The pilot, Gobel James, ejected and
was captured. He was released, but never knew what happened to
Martin.
   In 1974, the Air Force declared Martin dead. Last July, his body
was one of three of U.S. servicemen returned to the United States
by the Vietnamese government. The body was positively identified in
October.
   Mourners packed a United Methodist Church in this northeast
Kansas town of about 800 people for Saturday's funeral service. The
Rev. Edward Bateman, an Air Force chaplain, presided.
   An American flag covered Martin's casket. His photo and several
medals were placed just behind it.
   ``We never did give up hope,'' said Martin's brother, James.
``We always thought he was just a prisoner, that he would just come
home.''
   Martin said the return of his brother's body ``removes the
doubt. The knowing is always better than the wondering.''
   ``I feel very good about Larry being home today,'' Sheridan
said. ``It kind of settles part of my life, too.''
   At the cemetery, an Air Force detachment fired a 21-gun salute
and ``Taps'' was played.
   Air Force Maj. Mike Halloran presented the flag from Martin's
casket to the flier's mother, Ruth.
   ``It's another sad chapter put to rest,'' Halloran said.
</TEXT>
