<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Terris     11-18 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Terris,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Show Boat' Star Dies at 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norma Terris, who rocketed to stardom in the
original production of the musical ``Show Boat,'' has died after a
brief illness. She was 87.
   Miss Terris died Wednesday at her summer home in Lyme, Conn. She
also had a home in Palm Beach, Fla.
   The Columbus, Kan., native won critical acclaim for her
performance as Magnolia in the Florenz Ziegfeld production of
``Show Boat,'' which was written by Jerome Kern and Oscar
Hammerstein II. It opened on Broadway in 1927 and ran for 2{ years.
   Kern and Hammerstein wrote ``Why Do I Love You?'' _ one of the
show's enduring songs _ for Miss Terris during rehearsals.
   In 1932, she repeated her success in a Broadway revival of
``Show Boat.''
   Miss Terris appeared in Hollywood movies in the 1930s. During
the '30s and '40s she was a star of St. Louis' Municipal Opera
Company.
   Miss Terris was a member of the board of the Goodspeed Opera
House Foundation in Chester, Conn., for 30 years. She also sang
there occasionally.
   In 1984, Goodspeed opened the Norma Terris Theater, dedicated to
developing new musicals.
   Miss Terris established a fund to encourage performing artists
and composers, and endowed an intern program at the Goodspeed for
young people starting theatrical careers.
   A devoted animal lover, she donated 30 acres in East Haddam,
Conn., to the Humane Society for a nature center and regional
office.
   Miss Terris is survived by her husband, Albert D. Firestone.
</TEXT>
