<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlabamaExecution     11-18 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alabama Execution,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama Man Executed For Slaying Cousin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATMORE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The electrocution of Arthur James Julius
early Friday marked the fourth death warrant carried out in Alabama
this year, putting the state's execution rate at a level not seen
in 35 years.
   Following Julius' execution for the 1978 murder-rape of his
cousin, Prison Commissioner Morris Thigpen said the rate of
executions could increase.
   ``I think it is obvious with the number we have on death row,''
said Thigpen at a news conference following Julius' execution.
   The state now has 108 inmates under sentence of death.
   Julius, 43, dressed in a white sweatsuit and shower shoes, gave
two thumbs-up signs and waved both hands after his final words were
spoken to Holman Prison warden Charlie Jones, who read the death
warrant.
   Thigpen quoted Julius as saying ``he believed in God and knew he
would not let him suffer.''
   Julius, of Birmingham, was sentenced to death for the slaying of
his cousin, 29-year-old Susie Bell Sanders, at her Montgomery
apartment. He was on an pass from a prison work-release center at
the time. He was then serving a life term for a 1972 murder.
   Julius was the fourth inmate to die in Alabama's electric chair
this year and the 119th person put to death in the United States
since the 1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling allowing states to resume
use of the death penalty.
   The last time Alabama had four or more executions in one year
was 1954, when three convicted murderers and one rapist were put to
death in the electric chair at the old Kilby Prison in Montgomery.
Two of those executions were held on the same day.
</TEXT>
