<HEAD>Bush Meets With Civil Rights Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of civil rights leaders met with
President Bush on Friday to air ``honest differences'' and emerged
from the session giving the president high marks for listening.
   ``I think we all feel that we have succeeded in opening up a
dialogue on a number of issues,'' said Corretta Scott King, head of
the Martin Luther King Jr. Center.
   The widow of the slain civil rights leader said Bush was
``receptive to our ideas, even if he disagrees ... on some things,
many things perhaps.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the meeting, which
lasted about half an hour, had been requested by the Black
Leadership Forum.
   ``What we had to bring to the president represents a recognition
that it's in the best interest of the whole country as well as
African Americans that we achieve parity. We would hope for it in
the year 2000,'' said Dorothy Height of the National Council of
Negro Women.
   ``I think the most significant thing was that he listened, that
he showed a genuine interest, that we had real dialogue,'' she
added. ``There are honest differences of opinion on a number of
things.''
   Jospeh Lowery of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference
told reporters after the meeting that Bush was ``surprised to hear
that there was really overt racisim and he hoped it wasn't true.
But we gave him instances where we think it is true.''
   ``We're also concerned about covert racisim that puts this
invisible ceiling in the corporate community on where blacks can
rise to higher paying jobs,'' Lowery said.
