<FIRST>r w AM-Pilon     11-18 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilon,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice to Review Complaint From Former Employee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Friday it will
review a complaint that its internal disciplinary unit wrongly
described the results of a foreign counterintelligence
investigation of a former official.
   Department spokesman David Runkel said the agency will review
Roger Pilon's complaint that the Office of Professional
Responsiblility erred when it said the investigation produced
sufficient evidence to dismiss Pilon.
   Pilon says he was cleared of allegations that he gave South
Africa a classified document and was reinstated in his job at the
Justice Department.
   ``Obviously there is a difference of opinion on the facts and
that has to be looked at,'' Runkel said, adding that the matter
would be reviewed by Deputy Attorney General Donald Ayer.
   Pilon's lawyers have asked the department for a public apology
for what they called the report's ``egregiously inaccurate''
description of the investigation by the FBI and the Office of
Professional Responsiblility (OPR).
   Three House members also called on the Justice Department to
resolve the discrepancy between the Nov. 9 OPR report and the
evidence Pilon produced that he was cleared of the allegations and
reinstated with his security clearance.
   OPR's report said that while the counterintelligence
investigation ``did not develop sufficient evidence to support a
prosecution'' it ``did discover that sufficient cause existed to
terminate'' Pilon as head of the Office of Asylum Policy and Review.
   Following the report's release on Nov. 9, Pilon produced a Sept.
9, letter from a senior department official saying that he was
being reinstated to his job.
   Pilon said his security clearance was fully restored when he
returned to the department following an administrative leave.
   The report, which did not identify Pilon by name, said that he
resigned before ``the initiation of removal proceedings.''
   Pilon says he resigned only after his reinstatement, carrying
out a longterm plan to join the Cato Institute, a libertarian think
tank where he is now a fellow.
   Pilon confirms that he was the subject of an FBI
counterintelligence investigation that grew out of a background
check of his wife, Juliana, when she was considered to be an
assistant interior secretary.
   The investigation scuttled her nomination and resulted in what
Pilon calls a ``Kafkaesque nightmare.''
   Pilon denies the allegation that when he worked for the State
Department in 1987 he gave his wife a classified document on
communist influence in South Africa that was relayed to a South
African diplomat.
   In their letter to Thornburgh, the three members of the House
Judiciary Committee also asked Thornburgh in a letter to study the
case and ``if appropriate'' issue an apology.
   ``Obviously there is a discrepancy that deserves to be
resolved,'' said Reps. Don Edwards, D-Calif., Gerry Sikorski,
D-Minn., and Constance Morella, R-Md.
   ``If the facts are as the Pilons allege, then they have been
done an injustice by the inclusion of Roger's case in the OPR
report issued last week,'' the lawmakers said.
</TEXT>
