<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Soccer     11-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soccer,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns Convictions of Three Involved in Soccer Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge, questioning police evidence, overturned
the convictions of three men for violence at soccer games and
reduced the prison term Friday of a fourth man.
   Judge Lord Lane ruled that handwriting experts cast doubt on the
veracity of statements made by undercover policemen.
   On Thursday, the judge overruled the convictions of Vincent
Drake, 25, who was serving a seven-year sentence, and Terry Last,
26, and Stephen Hickmott, 33, both serving 10-year sentences, on
charges of plotting to fight.
   The case involved lengthy investigations, with undercover
officers trying to get close to people suspected of organizing
violence at soccer matches. Submitted as part of the evidence were
notes the officers often scribbled hastily.
   Judge Lane said police handwriting experts found that the notes
included dates and times of statements that did not match those on
officer duty sheets, suggesting tampering. He said that was
sufficient to undermine the prosecution's credibility.
   On Friday, Lane ruled that the six-year jail term of convicted
soccer hooligan Douglas Welsh, 25, was too long. Walsh has served
two years and the judge reduced the sentence to four years. That
will enable Walsh to be freed immediately under parole provisions.
   The judge said the violence that followed the 1986 cup final at
Wembley was terrifying but a six-year sentence flouted Appeal Court
guidelines and was too long.
   Five conspiracy cases involving soccer violence have collapsed
over the last two years with charges dropped against about 120
people. Scotland Yard was expected to begin an internal
investigation after the latest rulings.
   British soccer has been plagued by spectator violence in recent
years. A total of 39 people, most of them Italian fans, died when
rioting broke out among fans at a European soccer cup final match
between the British team Liverpool and Juventus from Turin, Italy,
at Heysel Stadium in Brussels on May 29, 1985. Drunken Liverpool
fans were blamed for starting the violence.
   Violent incidents at British soccer matches this year have
included street battles in Glasgow, Scotland, between rival
Scottish and English fans in which more than 250 people were
arrested.
</TEXT>
