<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Estonia     11-18 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Estonia,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonia Parliament Compromises on Election Law That Spawned Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Estonian parliament on Friday compromised on
an election law that spawned nine days of strikes by ethnic
Russians and other non-natives who feared lengthy residency
requirements would deprive them of the right to vote.
   The new law requires a 10-year residency in Estonia for holding
public office, but deletes a two-year residency requirement for the
right to vote, Tass said.
   It passed with 186 votes in favor, and 40 abstentions by the
``Equal Rights'' group of deputies, Tass said. It did not say if
anyone voted against the bill.
   In August, tens of thousands of Russians and other non-Estonian
residents of the Baltic republic walked off their jobs to protest
the law requiring two years' residence in Estonia to vote.
   The national Presidium called the law unconstitutional, but the
Estonian parliament, in an act of defiance, only suspended the
law's provisions for the local elections set for Dec. 10.
   The law passed Friday also requires candidates to live or work
in the district they hope to represent, a departure from current
national law. Many Soviet legislators, especially those well known,
represent districts far from their homes.
</TEXT>
