<HEAD>House Moves To Let Chinese Students Stay In United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 6th graf: ``The Attorney,'' to note forced departures
suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved compromise legislation
Friday aimed at protecting Chinese students in the United States
from reprisals at home for their participation in the pro-democracy
movement.
   By a voice vote, the House approved a House-Senate compromise
under which the 32,000 Chinese students holding ``exchange
visitor'' visas would not have to return home for two years before
applying for a change in their immigration status.
   The restriction had been intended to prevent a ``brain drain''
from developing nations, especially since students from abroad are
funded significantly by their own government.
   The bill requires that Chinese students holding the exchange
visitor visas, also known as ``J visas,'' to apply for immigration
status within four years of the bill's enactment.
   The compromise was reached Friday afternoon. The Senate must
still approve the report.
   The Attorney General has already suspended enforcement of
departures as a result of the Chinese government's suppression of
Chinese student protesters.
   As part of the compromise, the bill would require the Justice
Department to give careful consideration to applications by Chinese
nationals who express a fear of persecution because of China's
family planning law limiting couples to one child.
   Sen. William L. Armstrong, R-Colo., had asked for a provision to
protect Chinese nationals who refuse to practice birth control or
have an abortion in order to carry out the policy.
   The provision would cover applications for asylum, for
withholding of deportation or for refugee status.
</TEXT>
