<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-FEMAEstimates     11-18 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-FEMA Estimates,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debris Removal Costs Swell FEMA Aid Estimates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated cost of helping local
governments remove debris from Hurricane Hugo has increased by 50
percent to $90 million, the Federal Emergency Management Agency
said Friday.
   The total estimated cost of the storm to all FEMA programs has
increased to more than $437 million, of which $210 million will go
to public assistance programs, the agency said.
   In that category, FEMA has increased its estimate for debris
removal from $60 million to $90 million. In addition, estimated
assistance to public utilities has increased from $60 million to
$80 million.
   In a brief statement announcing the revised estimates, the
agency did not explain the reason for the increases.
   In addition to public assistance programs, which allocate money
to publicly owned or private non-profit organizations, the total
cost figure comprises an estimated $74 million toward individual
assistance programs such as housing repairs and medical costs; $53
million in low-interest loans; $70.9 million in mental health,
disaster unemployment and emergency food stamp costs; and $40
million to the military and other federal agencies.
</TEXT>
