<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-89 0156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PropaneFire     11-18 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Propane Fire,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Extinguished, Residents Return Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire crews injected water into a
300-foot-long propane pipeline Friday to extinguish a towering
day-long blaze, enabling nearly half of the town's 1,000 residents
to return to their homes.
   A smaller fire continued to burn Friday night at the Williams
Pipe Line Co. terminal, but it posed no danger and was being
allowed to burn out, company spokesman Jim Gipson said.
   ``The main fire is out and the line has been capped,'' Gipson
said.
   The fire started Thursday as a work crew was performing routine
maintenance on a pump at the plant two miles south of Jasper in
southwest Missouri, Gipson said. Flames had shot 200 feet into the
air from a 2-inch valve in the pipeline, which leads to a 17-acre
underground storage cavern.
   No one was injured and the cause remained undetermined, he said.
Five vehicles at the site were destroyed, he added.
   Pipeline fire experts from Texas and Oklahoma extinguished the
fire late Friday morning.
   Several hours later, about 500 residents who were evacuated from
a two-mile radius of the plant on Thursday were allowed to return
home. Many had stayed with friends and relatives or gone to
shelters in the nearby Lamar, Carthage and Joplin.
   A 10-mile stretch of U.S. 71 between Jasper and Carthage also
was reopened Friday afternoon, the State Highway Patrol said. The
plant lies several hundred yards from the highway.
   Flames continued to shoot from a valve on a 20,000-gallon
propane tank near the capped pipeline. The main blaze heated the
tank and popped an emergency release valve designed for that
purpose, officials said.
   Dairy farmer Randy Greene, who lives about a mile from the
plant, said he was happy to be able to return home and milk his
cows on schedule. The sky had an eerie orange glow to it when he
was allowed past barricades Thursday night to milk the herd, he
said.
   ``I was a little nervous being that close to the plant, but it
had to be done,'' he said.
</TEXT>
