<FIRST>r a AM-SalvadoranPriests-USReax     11-18 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvadoran Priests-US Reax,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slayings of Six Jesuits Mourned as `Victory for Extremism'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic officials urged the Bush administration to press
for an investigation of the killings of six Jesuit priests in El
Salvador and to stem the flow of arms to both sides in the civil
war.
   ``We have been sickened and outraged at the murders of the six
Jesuit priests and their co-workers as well as the more than 500
deaths that have occurred in El Salvador this past week,'' said a
statement from some 600 priests of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese
of Los Angeles.
   ``We ask that this violence be stopped. Ten years and 80,000
deaths have proven that the military solution is no solution,'' the
group, which included several exiles from El Salvador, said in the
statement drafted late Thursday at a meeting in Palm Springs.
   Earlier Thursday, Los Angeles Archbishop Roger Mahony called the
slayings wanton murder and asked the U.S. government to urge ``an
immediate truce, prompt negotiations between the government and the
guerrillas in El Salvador and the cessation of outside military
armaments to all sides.''
   Dozens of religious workers, labor activists, academics and
political figures went into hiding Friday in San Salvador after the
killings of the Jesuits and the arrest of 12 Lutheran missionaries.
The Lutherans, including four Americans, were released Friday
unharmed, the U.S. Embassy said.
   The slayings Thursday of Ignacio Ellacuria, rector of Jose
Simeon Canas Central American University, vice-rector Ignacio
Martin Baro, four other Jesuit priests, their housekeeper and her
15-year-old daughter were blamed on right-wing forces and drew
international condemnation.
   The National Council of Churches, America's largest religious
federation, urged Congress to halt delivery of military aid to El
Salvador.
   In Washington, Archbishop Daniel Pilarczyk, president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, wrote President Bush to
demand that the Salvadoran government be pressed to investigate.
   President Alfredo Cristiani, whose government denied any
responsibility, said he had ordered an inquiry.
   The slayings shocked even those accustomed to analyzing events
in the war-torn country.
   ``This was not the work of madmen. This was the work of cruel,
politically sophisticated men,'' said Richard Nuccio, author of
``Who's Wrong, Who's Right in Central America'' and an associate of
the Washington D.C.-based Inter-American Dialogue.
   Beatriz Manz, a Central American specialist at Wellesley College
in Boston, attributed the massacre to forces within Cristiani's
ruling party.
   ``It will intimidate the few voices of dissent, the few voices
of reason, in El Salvador,'' she said.
   Nuccio said ``we'll probably never know for sure'' who did the
killings, but he said they will ``make it very difficult for
Congress to give aid to El Salvador without attaching any
conditions on human rights violations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
