<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     11-18 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0968</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $31,000-plus pay raise for the House _ but
only $8,900 for the Senate _ is on its way to President Bush's desk
after careening through Congress in just two days.
   The Senate voted 56-43 Friday night to approve the bill, but
only after deciding at the last minute that it couldn't take the
poltical risk of the bigger House-passed pay raise. Instead,
senators would keep taking honoraria from interest groups, a
much-criticized practice eliminated by the House.
   ``We have done exactly the wrong thing tonight. We have
failed,'' said Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo.
   But the Senate didn't cut back the raise that applies to the
House, federal judges and top government executives, and the House
early today gave the measure final approval and shipped the package
to the president. The House gave its approval in a voice vote at
nearly 1:30 a.m. with whistling and cheers in the chamber.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators from the House and Senate are
calling for repeal of catastrophic health coverage for retirees and
nearing agreement on a compromise deficit-reduction package.
   Final action on those two bills, which could come Sunday, would
free Congress to adjourn for the year.
   Senior tax-writers in both houses agreed early today to kill the
catastrophic program, which was enacted with great fanfare less
than 18 months ago in an effort to protect retirees from being
bankrupted by costs of a major illness.
   But two Republican senators who had wanted to scale back the
program said they will work to defeat the repeal agreement. Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., promised to use every parliamentary tactic
available in an effort to prevent repeal, which he said would be an
incredible injustice.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a million East Germans poured into
West Berlin and West Germany, window-shopping or snacking on
bratwurst to celebrate the second weekend of their new-found
freedom to travel.
   In East Berlin, the new Communist premier outlined a mixture of
free enterprise and socialist planning to rescue his country from
its economic morass.
   Premier Hans Modrow, speaking Friday in his first address to
Parliament, also submitted a 28-member Cabinet for approval. It
gives 11 seats to non-Communist allies but retains the key posts of
foreign affairs, defense and economic affairs for the Communists.
   Almost half of the 1.2 million East Germans who came West late
Friday were in West Berlin, city officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, steering clear of the
controversial subject of German reunification, is making a
concerted show of consulting with Western leaders before his
shipboard summit with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The White House issued a statement Friday saying Bush had called
French President Francois Mitterrand and Canadian Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney on Friday, and had received a call from West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Another statement was issued later to report Bush had called
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and to say they will
continue their talks when they meet next Friday at Camp David, the
presidential retreat in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains.
   The leaders talked about the meeting this weekend of European
leaders on the fast-moving developments in Eastern Europe and
Bush's summit with Gorbachev Dec. 2 and 3 on ships off the coast of
Malta, the White House said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third of this capital's 1
million people were reportedly trapped without food and water after
a week of fighting between leftist rebels and government troops.
   Journalists in the eastern provincial capital of San Miguel
reported heavy fighting in that city and on a nearby bridge Friday
night. They had no estimates of deaths or injuries in the city 85
miles east of the capital.
   Hospital and military sources say more than 800 people have been
killed and and 2,000 wounded since the Marxist-led rebels launched
the offensive against the rightist government on Nov 11.
   There was a lull in the fighting in San Salvador on Friday night
and early today, with only occasional bursts of gunfire. However,
the capital has suffered the worst fighting of the 10-year-old
civil war over the past week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion-rights supporters say they are
setting the stage for next year's congressional battle with a bill
that would write into law the 1973 Roe vs. Wade Supreme Court
ruling that legalized abortion.
   ``This bill is going to be the rallying point,'' said Rep.
Claudine Schneider, R-R.I.
   Bills were introduced in the House and Senate on Friday that
would effectively overcome the Supreme Court decision last summer
in the so-called Webster case that gave states greater authority to
restrict abortions, supporters said.
   Just a few lines long, the bill would forbid states from
restricting a woman's right to have an abortion before the time her
fetus becomes viable for life outside the womb, or at any time when
necessary to protect the life of the mother.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Department officials say they realize
the federal government has mishandled Indian affairs and welcome a
Senate report that recommends allowing tribes to govern themselves.
   ``Quite clearly the federal government in the past has not been
as efficient, as careful or as caring as it should have been in a
number of instances,'' Frank Bracken, Interior undersecretary, said
Friday.
   But he said the department already has begun to correct problems
identified in a 238-page report released by a special investigating
panel of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs.
   The report summarizes a two-year investigation into government
corruption relating to Indians.
</TEXT>
