<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance for weekend editions, Nov. 18-19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Western Companies Looking Cautiously Toward Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. companies don't want to miss out on
opportunities in Eastern Europe, but they are moving with caution,
as General Electric Co. signaled this past week with its investment
in a Hungarian light bulb maker.
   GE's $150 million purchase of a 50 percent stake in Tungsram was
labeled as one of the biggest U.S. investments to date in Eastern
Europe, but in fact it was not especially large.
   The sum was dwarfed by GE's announcement on Friday of plans to
spend $10 billion over the next five years on repurchasing its own
stock. GE Chairman John Welch described the Hungarian investment as
a ``prudent risk'' _ not a head-over-heels plunge.
   There are good reasons for caution. Communist political systems
appear to be crumbling, but the bloody suppression of protest in
China this past June is a reminder that an authoritarian reaction
remains possible.
   Also, the currencies of Eastern Europe, as in the Soviet Union,
are non-convertible, meaning it is difficult for Western companies
to take profits home from their joint ventures.
   The positive side is that Eastern Europe is not only a huge
potential market for consumer and capital goods, but a source of
inexpensive, relatively well-educated workers _ a point recognized
by General Electric.
   GE has bigger plans than selling light bulbs to Hungarians.
Welch told analysts and reporters Friday that the company hopes to
export lighting systems from Hungary to Western Europe, a market it
has so far been unable to crack because of the domination of NV
Philips and Siemens AG.
   GE recognized that too much caution is dangerous, too, because
there is a limited number of healthy potential business partners in
Eastern Europe.
   ``To some extent the choice spots will be taken by those who are
there first,'' said Peter J. Pettibone, a partner in the New York
law firm of Lord Day &amp; Lord, Barrett Smith.
   Western European companies have a built-in advantage over
Americans when it comes to selling to and investing in Eastern
Europe because of the geographic and cultural closeness.
   Less obviously, the Western Europeans have a banking advantage.
The biggest American banks were burned by foolish lending to Latin
America and are neither willing nor able to make a big plunge into
Eastern Europe.
   West German banks, in contrast, are rich and willing, notes
Donald Wich, a New York marketing director for the German American
Chamber of Commerce. The German banks are more likely to lend to
companies from West Germany than to, say, an Eastman Kodak Co. or
Ford Motor Co.
   Volkswagen AG of West Germany produces car engines in East
Germany and Italy's Fiat produces cars in Poland for export to
Western Europe, but so far the West's embrace of the so-called Iron
Curtain nations has been less than wholehearted.
   The ferment in Eastern Europe has overshadowed the opportunities
in the Soviet Union, but developments also continued there this
past week. The Joint Commercial Commission met in Washington this
past week, bringing together Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher
and his Soviet counterpart, Konstantin Katushev, to discuss
lowering barriers to trade and investment.
   In spite of all the talk, investments in the Soviet Union remain
modest. The typical investment in U.S.-Soviet joint ventures is $3
million, according to a survey earlier this year by Lord Day &amp;
Lord, Barrett Smith.
   When Europe's ABB Asea Brown Boveri Ltd. bought Connecticut's
Combustion Engineering Inc. this past week for $1.6 billion, a
company executive said it was ``charging full speed ahead'' into
the East bloc.
   In fact, ABB gets less than 1 percent of its revenue in the
Eastern bloc and President Percy Barnevik told reporters he is
hoping to raise that to perhaps 3 percent to 3.5 percent.
   Yes, businesses are moving into Eastern Europe. But with caution.
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _Government reports indicated economic sluggishness. Reports
said factory utilization slumped to the lowest level in 1{ years
and retail sales sank by the biggest amount in 2{ years as auto
sales tumbled. A big drop in the trade deficit mainly was the
result of slowing imports, although exports rose.
   _Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. announced an expensive overhaul of its
credit-services operation after being embarrassed by widespread
customer complaints. It said the reforms would cut next year's
profits about a tenth. Analysts had been predicting an earnings
gain in 1990.
   _Delta Air Lines announced it would buy up to 260 jets from
McDonnell Douglas Corp. and Boeing Co. in a transaction that could
be worth more than $10 billion. Texas Air Corp. said its
Continental Airlines unit would buy $4.5 billion worth of jetliners
from Airbus Industrie, the European consortium.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv weekend editions Nov. 18-19</NOTE>
