<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 20,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday Nov 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Time Running Short For Year-End Tax Maneuvers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The waning weeks of the year provide
stock-market investors with a rare opportunity to look favorably on
their mistakes.
   Those shares you bought for $50 that now sell for $32 aren't
just a painful lesson in the risks of playing the market _ they're
a potential tax deduction!
   That may not be consolation enough to soothe your regrets over
the loss of some hard-earned capital. But it may be sufficient
reason to warrant taking some action before 1989 ends.
   If you transform a theoretical ``paper'' loss into an actual one
by selling the offending securities, the loss you realize
(including brokerage commissions you paid at both purchase and
sale) can be deducted without limit from any capital gains you had
during the year.
   People with more losses than gains, or no gains at all, can
deduct losses against their other income up to a maximum of $3,000
a year. Losses beyond that are carried forward to future years.
   Financial advisers urge anyone who is a candidate for year-end
maneuvers along these lines not to delay much longer.
   Depressed investments which are most likely choices for tax
selling often get further depressed in December when that tax
selling reaches its peak, they point out.
   In addition, they say, it may take a little time and planning to
decide what you want to do with the money you receive from the sale.
   The rules don't permit selling a security to realize a loss and
simultaneously buying it back. In fact, if the offsetting purchase
occurs any time within 30 days beforehand or afterward, it is
considered a ``wash sale'' and the loss can't be deducted.
   A common way to skirt this obstacle is to switch into some
similar security _ say, a stock of another company in a comparable
business with about the same business prospects.
   Switching is especially suited to bond investments, where you
can shop for a security of a different issuer with a yield,
maturity and credit rating much the same as the one you sold.
   William Brennan, editor of the Ernst &amp; Young Financial Planning
Reporter, advises would-be bond swappers, ``don't delay making a
decision until December. It takes time to find comparable bonds.''
   With stocks, switching is more problematic, since the
performances of individual companies' stock prices can be
drastically affected by a long list of variables.
   Furthermore, you still may consider the future bright for a
stock you own that has been a disappointment to date.
   If you want to take a deductible loss while sticking with that
stock, you have two primary choices _ sell it now and buy it back
31 days later, or buy another chunk now and sell the original
holding after 31 days have passed.
   The alternative of buying another chunk now protects you against
the risk that the stock might suddenly soar while you have
temporarily stepped aside. But it demands prompt action for any
losses you want to take in 1989.
   Any good broker should be ready and eager to help you through
the process of taking judicious tax losses _ as well as suggesting
strategies for postponing capital gains into 1990.
   After all, year-end tax transactions are a time-tested source of
commission revenue for the broker and his or her firm.
   That's a point worth bearing in mind for the customer as well as
the broker. The research devoted to any year-end tax planning
should include an appraisal of whether the tax savings achieved are
worth the transaction costs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon Nov 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
