<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv18-19   11-18 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 18-19,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 18-19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Gleaming Brighter For Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors spooked by the stock market have taken to precious
metals, a fact reflected by the sparkling performance of the gold,
silver and platinum markets in the past week.
   The rise in prices also has caught the attention of jewelry
makers and other commercial consumers of precious metals, whose
higher-volume buying underscores the consensus among analysts that
prices are unlikely to lapse to the relatively low levels that have
prevailed for much of this year.
   The price of gold, traditionally the bellwether of the precious
metals complex, has jumped nearly 8 percent in the five weeks since
the stock market's 190-point plunge on Oct. 13. Gold for December
delivery on New York's Commodity Exchange closed at $395.80 a troy
ounce Friday compared to $388.60 a week earlier.
   December silver soared to $5.685 an ounce from $5.26 during a
week of heavy trading on the Commodity Exchange while platinum for
January delivery on the New York Mercantile Exchange rose to
$526.60 an ounce from $509.60.
   Analysts closely are watching the gold market as an indicator of
the rally's underlying strength. A move above $400 an ounce, a key
psychological barrier last crossed in late January, likely would
bring new buyers into the market and push prices sharply higher.
   ``I suspect we'll see gold test the $400 level before the year's
end,'' said Bernard Savaiko, senior metals analyst with PaineWebber
Inc. in New York.
   Other analysts said the gold market seemed poised for a test of
$400 an ounce as early as next week.
   Precious metals, especially gold, traditionally are perceived as
a safe haven for investors during periods of rapid inflation or
economic uncertainty, when it is considered more likely to hold its
value than paper currencies or stocks.
   Analysts say the stock market's volatility has made U.S.
investors nervous enough to move some of their dollars into
precious metals. Meanwhile, the far-reaching political and social
changes occurring in Eastern Europe have stirred fears of economic
trouble among European investors and driven them to the gold and
silver markets as well.
   ``You're seeing a lot of retail buying from investors who have
stood on the sidelines for two years,'' said Bruce L. Kaplan,
president of Kaplan &amp; Co., a Los Angeles-based metals and coins
dealer. ``The money seems to be coming out of the stock and bond
markets.''
   Experts also have noted heavy buying of precious metals by
Japanese interests in the past week, perhaps reflecting investor
uneasiness in the Far East or stockpiling by Japanese jewelers.
   ``You can never underestimate the potential demand from Japan
for both platinum and gold,'' Savaiko said. Platinum is the most
popular jewelry metal in Japan.
   Platinum got an additional boost from the mid-week release of
revised 1989 supply and demand projections by London-based Johnson
Matthey PLC, the world's largest platinum refiner.
   Johnson Matthey predicted world platinum consumption would
outstrip production by 120,000 ounces this year, which would make
1989 the fifth straight year of deficit production and falling
warehouse stocks.
   The silver market showed remarkable strength Wednesday through
Friday. Analysts said the market was playing catch-up with gold and
platinum after lagging behind those markets.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Grains and Soybeans</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The grain and soybean markets exhibited slight but steady
strength through most of the week. The gains were largely seasonal,
reflecting the end of the corn and soybean harvest and a shift in
the market's attention from supply to demand concerns.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Energy</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices were little changed on the week. Strength in the
heating oil and crude oil markets late in the week was linked to
wintry weather in the Northeast and to speculation that an
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries meeting beginning
Saturday in Vienna could lead to lower crude-oil production
ceilings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Livestock and Meat</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Prices were little changed, although prospects for more U.S.
food aid to Poland continued supporting the pork markets. A monthly
Agriculture Department report released after the close of trading
Friday showed three percent fewer cattle on feedlots Nov. 1 than on
the same date a year ago. Although that number was near market
expectations, the report also showed an unexpectedly large number
of feedlot placements last month. That was expected to prompt
fairly heavy selling of live cattle futures when trading resumes
Monday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
